Value-based care: outcomes/cost. Transition FFS → P4P → APM. MIPS + ACOs (MSSP, REACH). PCF. Bundled payments. Population health infrastructure. Quality + cost + equity measures. High-value care examples. Practice transformation. Challenges + future. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Adolescent Integrative Comprehensive Care (AAP + SAHM + AAFP):

(1) Adolescent-specific assessment HEEADSSS: Home + Education/Employment + Eating + Activities + Drugs + Sexuality + Suicide/depression + Safety; comprehensive social + behavioral;

(2) Confidentiality + consent: - Discuss limits + boundaries upfront; - Confidential time alone with adolescent (without parent) starting around age 12; - Sensitive services laws vary by state — most allow confidential care for mental health, sexual + reproductive health, substance use; - Mandatory reporting limits confidentiality: abuse, suicide/homicide risk, certain infections;

(3) Mental health screening: - PHQ-9 adolescent (PHQ-A) — universal screening; - Suicide screening (ASQ, Columbia) — high mortality cause adolescent; - Anxiety (GAD-7, SCARED); - Eating disorders (SCOFF); - Substance use (CRAFFT 2.1+); - ADHD if concerns; - Bullying including cyber; - LGBTQ+ identity + acceptance; - Body image + body composition; - Trauma + ACEs;

(4) Sexual + reproductive health: - SSHADESS (Sexual orientation, behaviors, partners, practices); - STI screening risk-based; HIV, HCV per CDC; - Contraception counseling — LARC most effective + safe adolescent; emergency contraception; - HPV vaccination; - Pregnancy testing if applicable + options counseling (non-directive); - LGBTQ+-affirming care including gender-diverse + transgender support; - Healthy relationships + IPV;

(5) Substance use: - Universal CRAFFT screening; - Tobacco / vaping (rising concern); - Alcohol; - Marijuana (legal status varies); - Other substances including opioid + stimulant; - Brief intervention (SBIRT); - Treatment referral (counseling, MOUD for OUD);

(6) Nutrition + activity + sleep + screen: 5-2-1-0 (5 fruits/veg, < 2 h screen, 1 h activity, 0 sugary drinks); athletic considerations; eating disorder screen;

(7) Driving safety + injury prevention; firearms, helmets, drugs/alcohol;

(8) Vaccinations: HPV, meningococcal (ACWY + B), Tdap, flu, COVID, RSV; catch-up;

(9) Chronic condition management: developmental tasks of adolescence + chronic illness (DM, asthma, mental health) — transition planning;

(10) Transition to adult care: 14-26 yo gradual process; transition policy; teach self-management skills; communication with adult provider; written summary;

(11) Family involvement balance: developmentally appropriate, respect autonomy + family role; family-centered when possible; family therapy when needed;

(12) School + community resources: 504, IEP, school counselor, sports, community mentors, mental health resources;

(13) Trauma-informed care + ACEs; LGBTQ+ minority stress;

(14) Reproductive + parental considerations for minors (in care, foster, juvenile justice);

(15) Multidisciplinary integrative: PCP + adolescent medicine + behavioral health + nutrition + school + family + community + reproductive health + LGBTQ+ resources + addiction services
————————————————
Adolescent integrative care: HEEADSSS, confidential time, sensitive topics. Mental health (PHQ-A, suicide, EDs, substance — CRAFFT). Sexual + repro health + LGBTQ+ affirming. Vaccinations + lifestyle. Transition to adult care. Family balance. Trauma-informed. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Chronic Pain Integrative Management (CDC 2022 Pain Guideline + ACP):

(1) Comprehensive biopsychosocial assessment: - Pain characterization, neuropathic features, central sensitization; - Functional impact (work, ADL, mood, sleep, relationships); - Mental health (depression, anxiety, PTSD common comorbid); - Substance use; - Trauma + ACEs; - SDOH; - Treatment history + response;

(2) Multimodal approach core principle — multiple modalities address multiple mechanisms: - Active management + patient self-management central;

(3) Non-pharmacologic FIRST + foundation: - Movement / exercise — aerobic, strength, flexibility (yoga, tai chi); strong evidence chronic pain; - PT — manual therapy, exercise; - CBT for chronic pain — strong evidence; available in-person + digital; - Acceptance + Commitment Therapy (ACT); - Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction (MBSR); - Acupuncture — strong evidence many conditions; - Massage; - Sleep optimization — CBT-I, hygiene; - Stress management; - Heat / cold; - Patient education + pain neuroscience education;

(4) Pharmacologic — non-opioid first + scheduled multimodal: - Acetaminophen + NSAIDs (topical + oral) cautious; - Antidepressants: - SNRI (duloxetine, milnacipran) — neuropathic + fibromyalgia + chronic MSK + depression; - TCA (amitriptyline, nortriptyline) — neuropathic + sleep + chronic pain; cautious cardiac; - SSRI less effective for pain but useful comorbid depression; - Anticonvulsants (gabapentin, pregabalin) — neuropathic + fibromyalgia; sedation; - Topical: capsaicin, lidocaine, NSAIDs; - Cannabis / CBD — limited evidence variable, regulatory considerations; - Muscle relaxants short-term selected;

(5) Opioid considerations (CDC 2022 nuanced update from 2016): - For chronic pain — generally not first-line, but legitimate role for selected (cancer, end-of-life, palliative; selected chronic non-cancer when benefits outweigh harm); - Avoid abrupt discontinuation in established users — taper carefully (CDC 2022 critical update — 2016 misinterpretation caused harm); - Multimodal approach with opioids when used; - Lowest effective dose + duration; - Risk mitigation: PDMP check, UDS, naloxone co-Rx, treatment agreement, mental health screen; - Monitor function + pain + adverse effects; - Don't increase opioid for tolerance without reassessment; - OUD screening + treatment if applicable — MOUD (buprenorphine especially compatible with chronic pain); - Avoid combination opioid + benzo / gabapentinoid / sedative when possible (overdose risk);

(6) Interventional pain management selected: - Trigger point injections; - Epidural steroid injection (radiculopathy, short-term); - Facet RFA (refractory); - Joint injections; - Sympathetic blocks; - Spinal cord stimulation; - Intrathecal pumps (severe refractory);

(7) Mental health integration mandatory — depression + anxiety + PTSD + substance use treatment alongside pain — improves both; Collaborative Care Model;

(8) Address SDOH: work, finances, housing, social support, transportation;

(9) Family + caregiver involvement + support;

(10) Goals: function + quality of life > pain elimination; SMART goals;

(11) Self-management programs: Chronic Pain Self-Management Program (Stanford);

(12) Specialty referral: pain medicine, rehab medicine, behavioral health, addiction medicine;

(13) Multidisciplinary integrative: PCP + pain medicine + PT/OT + behavioral health + psychiatry + addiction medicine + pharmacy + family + community resources + complementary providers
————————————————
Chronic pain integrative: biopsychosocial. Non-pharm foundation (exercise, CBT, ACT, mindfulness, PT, acupuncture). Multimodal pharm (acetaminophen, NSAIDs, SNRI, TCA, gabapentinoids, topicals). Opioids selected + cautious (CDC 2022 nuanced). Mental health integration. SDOH. Function goals. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): LGBTQ+ + Transgender Primary Care (WPATH SOC 8 + AMA + Endocrine Society):

(1) Affirming care principles: - Use correct name + pronouns; - Avoid assumptions; - Inclusive intake forms (sexual orientation, gender identity, sex assigned at birth, pronouns); - Confidentiality + privacy; - Address minority stress + discrimination history; - Trauma-informed;

(2) Comprehensive primary care: - Routine preventive care per organs present (not gender identity): - Cervical CA screening if has cervix; - Breast screening if breast tissue (consider age + GAHT); - Prostate screening if has prostate; - Mental health — high rates depression, anxiety, suicide (especially adolescents) — supportive + affirming care reduces; Trevor Project, Trans Lifeline; - HIV / STI screening — risk-based, multi-site; - PrEP for high-risk MSM, trans women MSM; - Substance use — higher rates; - Vaccinations: HPV (all ages), HepA/B, COVID, Mpox high-risk; - Sexual + reproductive health — fertility considerations before GAHT/surgery + ongoing;

(3) Gender-affirming hormone therapy (GAHT) for transgender women (estrogen-based feminization, per WPATH SOC 8 + Endocrine Society): - Estrogen: estradiol (oral, transdermal, IM, SC); transdermal preferred for VTE + age + smoker; serum levels guide; goal premenopausal female range; - Anti-androgen: spironolactone first-line US (testosterone reduction + diuretic awareness K, BP); alternatives: cyproterone (not US), GnRH agonist (leuprolide — expensive); finasteride / dutasteride limited; - Progestin controversial — some add for chest development + libido (micronized progesterone); - Effects timeline education: breast development (3 mo - 2 yr), softer skin (3-6 mo), fat redistribution (3-6 mo), libido decrease (1-3 mo); permanent (breast growth, some genital) vs reversible (most others); - Monitoring: estradiol + testosterone q 3 mo year 1, then q 6-12 mo; lipids; LFT; glucose; K (if spironolactone); BP; mood; VTE risk; cardiovascular; bone (long-term); breast (if older + estrogen exposure);

(4) For transgender men: - Testosterone (IM, SC, transdermal, gel, pellet); - Effects: deepening voice (permanent), facial hair (permanent), clitoromegaly (permanent), menstruation cessation (1-6 mo), fat redistribution; - Monitoring: testosterone, lipid, Hct (erythrocytosis), LFT, BP, mental health; - Continued cervical + breast screening if applicable; - Contraception consideration if uterus + ovaries + sexual activity with sperm-producing partner (pregnancy possible despite testosterone);

(5) Surgical gender-affirming options: - Facial feminization / masculinization; - Top surgery (breast augmentation / mastectomy); - Bottom surgery (vaginoplasty, phalloplasty, metoidioplasty, hysterectomy + orophorectomy); - Voice surgery; - Body contouring; - Multidisciplinary care + experienced surgeons; - Specific post-op care + monitoring;

(6) Adolescent gender-affirming care (controversial politically, supported by major medical organizations): - WPATH SOC 8 adolescents: assessment by qualified clinician, consideration developmental + family, puberty blockers (GnRH agonists) for early-pubertal as reversible bridge, GAHT later, surgery generally adulthood (some exceptions); - Family + school + community support; - Mental health support; - Affirming care reduces suicide, depression, anxiety;

(7) Legal + ID changes — navigation;

(8) Insurance coverage — variable; advocacy;

(9) Mental health support — affirming therapist; specific resources;

(10) Family + community involvement;

(11) Multidisciplinary: PCP + endocrinology + mental health + surgery (multidisciplinary GAS team) + voice therapist + reproductive medicine + advocacy + community + family
————————————————
LGBTQ+ + transgender care: affirming + correct name/pronouns + inclusive forms. Preventive care per organs present. Mental health support critical. GAHT per WPATH SOC 8 — estrogen + anti-androgen feminization; testosterone masculinization. Adolescent GAC affirming. Surgical options. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Palliative Care in Primary Care (NHPCO + CAPC + Center to Advance Palliative Care):

(1) Palliative care = serious illness care — at any stage, alongside curative treatment; not just end-of-life; specialty workforce limited so primary care palliative care critical;

(2) Symptom management: - Pain — multimodal opioid + adjuvant; - Dyspnea — treat underlying + opioids low-dose effective + fan + position + O2 if hypoxic + benzo if anxiety component; - Nausea — etiology-targeted; - Constipation — universal opioid users; - Anorexia / cachexia — explore + avoid forced feeding; - Fatigue; - Anxiety + depression; - Insomnia; - Delirium; - Spiritual distress;

(3) Advance care planning (ACP): - Goals of care discussions (Serious Illness Conversation Guide); - POLST / MOLST actionable medical orders; - Advance directive + living will + healthcare POA; - Code status; - Surrogate decision-maker; - Cultural + religious considerations; - Five Wishes patient-friendly tool; - Ongoing conversations as conditions change;

(4) Hospice eligibility + referral: - Prognosis ≤ 6 mo if disease takes natural course; - Disease-specific guidelines (NHPCO LCD); - Medicare hospice benefit + most insurance; - Goals shift to comfort + quality of life; - Multidisciplinary team (MD, RN, SW, chaplain, aide, volunteer, bereavement); - Home, nursing facility, inpatient hospice, hospital; - Curative treatment generally discontinued (some integration emerging);

(5) HF-specific palliative: - Specific symptom management (diuretics, opioids for dyspnea, anxiolytics); - Device deactivation discussions (ICD, LVAD); - Disposition (home, hospice, LTAC); - Inpatient palliative consult for complex; - Specialist HF + palliative co-management;

(6) Caregiver support critical: - Education + skills training; - Respite care (in-home, adult day care, short-term residential); - Support groups + counseling; - Address caregiver burnout (Zarit Burden); - Family meetings; - Grief + bereavement support during + after; - Practical help (Meals on Wheels, transportation); - Financial counseling;

(7) Spiritual + cultural care: chaplain + faith community + cultural humility;

(8) Existential + emotional: meaning-making, life review, dignity therapy, art/music therapy, complementary practices;

(9) Coordinated transitions + communication across settings;

(10) Bereavement support for family — typically 13 months hospice;

(11) Pediatric palliative care + perinatal palliative care — specialized but similar principles;

(12) Equity in palliative + hospice access — disparities by race, ethnicity, geography, language; address;

(13) Provider self-care + grief — accumulating loss; debrief + support;

(14) Multidisciplinary integrative: PCP + palliative care specialist + hospice + cardiology (HF specialist) + nursing + social work + chaplain + caregivers + family + community + behavioral health + pharmacy + nutritionist + therapists
————————————————
Palliative care = serious illness care any stage. Symptom management (pain, dyspnea — opioids effective, NV, constipation, fatigue, mood). Advance care planning + hospice if ≤ 6 mo. HF-specific. Caregiver support critical. Spiritual + bereavement. Equity. Multidisciplinary integrative.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Thyroid Nodule Evaluation (ATA 2015):

(1) Initial workup: TSH + thyroid US for all palpable / incidentally discovered nodules;

(2) TSH-based approach: - TSH low/suppressed → radioiodine scan (hot nodule rarely malignant, hyperthyroid Rx if toxic); - TSH normal/elevated → US characterization;

(3) US classification (ACR TI-RADS or ATA sonographic patterns) stratifies malignancy risk + biopsy threshold: - TI-RADS 1-2 / Benign / Very low suspicion — no FNA; - TR3 / Low — FNA if ≥ 2.5 cm or follow if ≥ 1.5 cm; - TR4 / Intermediate — FNA if ≥ 1.5 cm; - TR5 / High suspicion — FNA if ≥ 1.0 cm; - High-risk features: solid hypoechoic, microcalcifications, irregular margins, taller-than-wide, extrathyroidal extension, suspicious LN;

(4) FNA biopsy (US-guided) — Bethesda system 6 categories: - I Non-diagnostic → repeat FNA; - II Benign → US surveillance 12-24 mo; - III AUS/FLUS → repeat FNA or molecular; - IV Suspicious for follicular neoplasm → lobectomy vs molecular; - V Suspicious for malignancy → surgery; - VI Malignant → surgery;

(5) Molecular testing (Afirma, ThyroSeq, ThyGeNEXT/ThyraMIR) for indeterminate (Bethesda III, IV) — reduces unnecessary surgery;

(6) Treatment: - Benign nodule — US surveillance + adjust intervals based on growth/changes; symptomatic / cosmetic → ethanol ablation / RF ablation / surgery; - Differentiated thyroid CA (papillary > follicular) — lobectomy vs total thyroidectomy ± LN dissection; RAI ablation selected; levothyroxine suppression; surveillance Tg + neck US; - Medullary — total thyroidectomy + central LN; calcitonin, CEA, RET mutation; - Anaplastic — aggressive, multimodal; - Lymphoma, metastatic — specific;

(7) Active surveillance for low-risk papillary microcarcinoma (< 1 cm, well-differentiated) — alternative to surgery selected (Ito + others);

(8) Pediatric: more likely malignant if found — refer endocrine + FNA threshold lower;

(9) Pregnancy: FNA OK; defer surgery if possible to postpartum; RAI contraindicated;

(10) Family history: MEN2 (medullary), FAP (PTC), Cowden — genetic considerations;

(11) Multidisciplinary: PCP + endocrinology + endocrine surgery + cytopathology + radiology + nuclear medicine
————————————————
Thyroid nodule: TSH + US for all. TI-RADS or ATA pattern guides FNA threshold (size + features). Bethesda categorization → management. Molecular testing for indeterminate. Surgical pathology directed treatment. Active surveillance selected. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Acute Uncomplicated Diverticulitis (AGA 2015 + 2022):

(1) Diagnosis: CT contrast preferred imaging (also assesses complications — abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction); WBC + CRP;

(2) Classification: uncomplicated vs complicated (abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction, peritonitis, hemorrhage);

(3) Treatment uncomplicated outpatient (selected patients): - Antibiotics — selective use (AGA 2015 update — not all patients need): - Consider observation without antibiotics in mild uncomplicated patients (AVOD + DIABOLO trials — no benefit antibiotic over supportive); - Reasonable: hospitalize / antibiotic if immunocompromised, comorbidity, elderly, complicated, can't tolerate PO, severe systemic; - If antibiotic — amoxicillin-clavulanate PO × 5-10 d (newer trials shorter courses) OR ciprofloxacin + metronidazole; - Hospital IV: ceftriaxone + metronidazole or pip-tazo;

(4) Diet: clear liquid early, advance as tolerated; no evidence prolonged restriction; no need to avoid nuts, seeds, popcorn long-term (historical myth);

(5) Follow-up + colonoscopy after acute episode: - Routine colonoscopy 4-8 wk after recovery for first episode in patients without recent colonoscopy — exclude malignancy (rates of CRC slightly elevated post-diverticulitis); evidence supports but some emerging modification for younger / clear-cut cases;

(6) Long-term management: - High-fiber diet + adequate hydration — recurrence prevention; - Physical activity + weight; - Avoid NSAIDs (perforation risk); - Smoking cessation; - Mesalamine + rifaximin + probiotics — limited evidence;

(7) Surgery (elective for recurrent or complicated, urgent for complications): - Elective sigmoidectomy — individualized based on recurrence frequency, severity, lifestyle impact, complicated episodes; previous threshold of 2 episodes no longer absolute (more individualized); - Complicated abscess: percutaneous drainage if > 4 cm; smaller may respond to antibiotics alone; - Perforation / peritonitis → urgent surgery (Hartmann's procedure traditional, primary anastomosis emerging);

(8) Complications watch: - Abscess; - Perforation (free air → emergency); - Fistula (colovesical most common — UTI, pneumaturia, fecaluria); - Obstruction; - Hemorrhage (separate diverticular bleed);

(9) Recurrence common (~ 30%);

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + GI + surgery + radiology + IR (drainage) + dietitian
————————————————
Acute uncomplicated diverticulitis: CT diagnosis. Outpatient OK selected — antibiotics selective (AGA 2015), often supportive sufficient. Colonoscopy 4-8 wk post for first. Long-term high-fiber + lifestyle. Surgery individualized. Watch complications. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Microscopic Hematuria Workup (AUA 2020):

(1) Diagnosis: ≥ 3 RBC/HPF on properly collected midstream urine confirmed on 1 of 2 urinalyses;

(2) Risk stratification AUA 2020 (replaces prior age-based): - Low risk: women < 50, men < 40, never smoker, < 10 RBC/HPF, no risk factors → repeat UA within 6 mo; if hematuria persists → reclassify; - Intermediate risk: 50-60 yo women, 40-60 yo men, 10-30 pack-yr smoking, 11-25 RBC/HPF, other risk factors → cystoscopy + renal US; - High risk (this patient): > 60 yo, > 30 pack-yr smoker, > 25 RBC/HPF, gross hematuria → cystoscopy + CT urography (CTU) — best test for upper tract;

(3) Rule out first: UTI (treat + repeat), exercise, menstruation, sexual activity, trauma, GU procedure recent;

(4) Workup: - Urinalysis confirm; - Urine culture rule out UTI; - Urine cytology — limited utility primary; useful selected (high-risk + cytology positive → urgent workup); - Imaging: - CT urography — gold standard upper tract (high-risk); - Renal US + KUB — alternative if CT contraindication / pregnancy / younger; - MRI urography alternative; - Cystoscopy — bladder evaluation (>= intermediate risk); - Cr / BUN, BP; - Proteinuria, dysmorphic RBC, casts suggest glomerular cause → nephrology workup (BMP, UPC, ANA, complement, hepatitis serology, etc.);

(5) Causes: - Urologic (workup priorities high-risk): malignancy (bladder, kidney, prostate, urethra), stones, BPH, infection, trauma, polycystic kidney; - Nephrologic / glomerular: IgA nephropathy, thin BM disease, Alport, glomerulonephritis (post-infectious, lupus, vasculitis), other; - Other: medications (rifampin, NSAIDs), exercise;

(6) Smoking cessation — bladder cancer major risk;

(7) Follow-up negative workup: repeat UA periodically (annual) — many resolve spontaneously; consider repeat workup if persistent + change in risk; nephrology referral if glomerular features;

(8) Bladder cancer high index suspicion smoker + hematuria — don't dismiss;

(9) Anticoagulation: doesn't excuse workup — anticoagulant-related hematuria still needs evaluation if persistent;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + urology + nephrology + radiology + smoking cessation
————————————————
Microscopic hematuria: AUA 2020 risk-stratified workup. High-risk (smoker, > 60, > 25 RBC) → cystoscopy + CT urography. Rule out UTI/menstruation first. Glomerular features → nephrology. Smoking cessation. Don't dismiss bladder CA. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Lumbar Radiculopathy / Sciatica Management (ACP + NASS):

(1) Diagnosis: history (radiating leg pain > back pain, dermatomal, exacerbated by Valsalva, sciatic stretch — SLR + crossed SLR), exam (neurologic — sensory, motor, reflexes); rule out cauda equina (saddle anesthesia, bladder/bowel) emergency;

(2) No imaging routinely first 4-6 wk unless red flags or progressive neuro deficit;

(3) Conservative management 4-6 wk first (most resolve within 3 mo without intervention): - Activity modification (avoid prolonged bed rest); - NSAIDs short-term; - PT — McKenzie method, core strengthening, neurodynamic mobilization; - Education + reassurance — favorable prognosis; - Heat / ice; - Avoid opioids as first-line (limited benefit + harms); - Gabapentin / pregabalin — modest evidence radicular pain (more for diabetic neuropathy); - Oral steroids — limited evidence for sciatica (METEOR trial — modest functional benefit); - Topical agents; - Acupuncture alternative;

(4) MRI lumbar indicated for: - Red flags (cauda equina, malignancy, infection, fracture); - Progressive neuro deficit; - Failed conservative ≥ 6 wk + considering interventional/surgical; - Atypical / suspicious;

(5) Epidural steroid injection (ESI): - Modest short-term benefit for radicular pain (NASS); - Transforaminal or interlaminar; - Image-guided (fluoroscopy / US); - 1-3 typically, no more than 3/yr; - Risks: rare but serious (infection, hematoma, paralysis with cervical TF approach);

(6) Surgery indications: - Cauda equina (emergent); - Progressive motor deficit (weakness); - Refractory disabling pain ≥ 6-12 wk + correlative imaging (microdiscectomy, decompression, sometimes fusion); - SPORT trial — surgery + conservative both effective long-term, surgery faster recovery;

(7) Yellow flags (psychosocial chronicity risk): fear-avoidance, depression, work issues — address;

(8) Return to activity + work modifications;

(9) Multimodal chronic if persistent — CBT, multidisciplinary pain program;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + PT + pain medicine + spine surgery (ortho or neurosurgery) + behavioral health
————————————————
Sciatica: rule out cauda equina. No imaging first 4-6 wk without red flags. Conservative (PT, NSAIDs, activity, education). MRI if red flags / refractory / progressive deficit. ESI selective. Surgery for emergent or refractory + correlative imaging. Yellow flags. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Bell's Palsy Management (AAN 2012 + AAO-HNS 2013):

(1) Diagnosis clinical: acute (< 72 h) peripheral CN VII palsy involving forehead (unlike central — preserves forehead); often unilateral; can include hyperacusis, decreased taste anterior 2/3 tongue, decreased lacrimation, postauricular pain;

(2) Differential — rule out before Bell's palsy diagnosis: - Central (stroke) — preserves forehead, other neuro deficits; - Lyme disease — bilateral facial palsy, endemic area, tick exposure, classic erythema migrans (50%) → serology (high prevalence area), treat doxycycline; - Ramsay Hunt syndrome (HZV) — vesicles in ear canal, severe pain, sometimes hearing loss / vertigo → acyclovir + steroid + urgent ENT; - Otitis media / mastoiditis; - Trauma / fracture; - Tumor (slowly progressive, recurrent, complete + atypical features → MRI); - Sarcoidosis, GBS, MS;

(3) Workup: clinical for typical; selected — Lyme serology endemic, HSV/VZV serology if vesicles, CBC, glucose, imaging if atypical/progressive/recurrent (MRI w/ contrast);

(4) Treatment — start within 72 h for best outcomes: - Prednisone 60 mg daily × 7 days then taper — Class I evidence (Engstrom, Sullivan); improves probability complete recovery; - Antiviral (acyclovir, valacyclovir) — controversial, possible modest benefit added to steroid in severe cases (Class II); use combination if severe (House-Brackmann ≥ IV) per some guidelines; not effective alone; - Eye care critical: lubricating drops daytime, ophthalmic ointment + taping/patch nighttime, eye protection; ophthalmology if persistent (risk corneal abrasion + ulceration); - Facial exercises / PT — may help recovery;

(5) Prognosis: - 70% complete recovery without treatment; - 85% with steroid; - Recovery 3 wk - 6 mo typically; - Persistent / synkinesis / facial spasm in 30%; - Worse prognosis: complete palsy, older, DM, HTN, taste loss, hyperacusis, postauricular pain severe;

(6) Refractory / no improvement: - Refer ENT / neurology / facial nerve specialist; - Electrodiagnostic studies (ENoG, EMG) 5-21 days post-onset for prognostic + decision on intervention; - Surgical decompression — selected severe nonimprovement (controversial); - Botox + selective neurectomy for late synkinesis; - Facial reanimation surgery;

(7) Recurrent or bilateral — investigate for underlying cause (Lyme, sarcoid, lymphoma, GBS);

(8) Pregnancy: 3x higher; usually 3rd trimester / immediate postpartum; treatment + close monitoring;

(9) Patient education + emotional support: facial appearance distressing;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + neurology + ENT + ophthalmology + PT + facial nerve specialist (refractory) + mental health if needed
————————————————
Bell's palsy: peripheral CN VII (forehead involved). Rule out central, Lyme, Ramsay Hunt. Treatment within 72 h: prednisone 60 mg × 7 d → taper. Antiviral selected for severe. Eye care critical. Prognosis good — most recover. Refractory specialist. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Anaphylaxis — Emergency (AAAAI + WAO 2020):

(1) Diagnosis: rapid-onset (minutes to hours) of skin/mucosa involvement + ≥ 1 of (respiratory, hypotension/end-organ, GI, syncope); OR hypotension/respiratory after known allergen exposure;

(2) TRIGGER first-line: IM epinephrine — DO NOT DELAY: - 0.3-0.5 mg adults (0.01 mg/kg, max 0.5 mg) IM into vastus lateralis (anterolateral thigh) — best absorption; - 0.15 mg child < 30 kg; - Repeat q 5-15 min if no improvement (~ 30% need repeat); - SC less effective than IM; - IV epinephrine drip for refractory in monitored setting only — high arrhythmia risk if bolus;

(3) Position: supine + legs elevated if hypotensive; left lateral if pregnant; sitting if dyspnea;

(4) Adjunct therapies (after epinephrine, not as substitute): - Oxygen + airway support; - IV fluid crystalloid bolus (20-30 mL/kg adult or 10-20 mL/kg child); - H1 antihistamine (diphenhydramine, cetirizine) — symptom relief skin only, NOT life-saving; - H2 antihistamine (famotidine) — symptom relief; - Inhaled bronchodilator (albuterol) for bronchospasm; - Corticosteroid (methylprednisolone 1-2 mg/kg IV) — debated efficacy in preventing biphasic, some evidence not helpful; given still by many;

(5) Refractory anaphylaxis: - IV epinephrine drip; - Vasopressors (norepinephrine, vasopressin); - Glucagon 1-5 mg IV (especially beta-blocker-blocked patients); - Methylene blue refractory shock;

(6) Observation post-event: - 4-6 hours typical mild; - 8-24+ hours severe; - Biphasic reactions in 5-20% (most within 4-6 h, can be up to 72 h); - Disposition based on clinical + risk;

(7) Discharge planning: - Epinephrine auto-injector prescription (≥ 2 devices) — patient + family + school; - Education on use; - Anaphylaxis action plan; - Trigger avoidance counseling; - Allergy referral for trigger identification + further management; - Medical alert identification; - No discharge without epinephrine prescription;

(8) Allergist evaluation: skin testing, specific IgE, oral food challenge, drug challenge (selected), component-resolved diagnostics;

(9) Immunotherapy / desensitization: - Venom immunotherapy highly effective (hymenoptera); - Oral immunotherapy (peanut — Palforzia) FDA-approved 4-17 yo; - Drug desensitization for required medications; - Aeroallergen SCIT/SLIT for allergic rhinitis (may reduce systemic);

(10) Specific allergen counseling: - Food: read labels, restaurant communication, school plans; - Drug: medical alert, listed on chart, alternatives; - Insect: avoidance, removal techniques; - Latex: occupational + medical; - Idiopathic anaphylaxis approach;

(11) Comorbidity: asthma well-controlled (highest mortality), mast cell disease (mastocytosis);

(12) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ED + allergy/immunology + emergency response + family + school + pharmacy
————————————————
Anaphylaxis: IM epinephrine IMMEDIATELY (0.3-0.5 mg vastus lateralis), repeat q 5-15 min if needed. Adjuncts (O2, IV fluid, H1/H2 antihistamine, bronchodilator, steroid) AFTER epi. Observation biphasic. Discharge with epi pen + plan + allergist referral. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Vaccine Hesitancy Counseling (CDC + AAP + AAFP):

(1) Common parental concerns: - Autism (myth from Wakefield retracted 1998 — extensively disproven across many large studies, > 1 million children); - Adverse events (most mild local, serious extremely rare per VAERS analyses); - 'Too many too soon' (immune system handles thousands antigens daily; combined vaccines safe + well-studied); - Disease 'natural'; - Pharmaceutical motivations / mistrust; - Ingredients (aluminum, thimerosal — removed from most childhood vaccines 2001 in US except multi-dose flu); - Religious / philosophical beliefs; - COVID-related amplification of hesitancy;

(2) Communication approach evidence-based: - Presumptive (not participatory) approach — recommend strongly + matter-of-factly: 'Today Sarah is due for MMR, varicella, and Hib' (vs 'What do you want to do?'); evidence improves uptake; - Motivational interviewing for hesitant parents — open-ended, reflective listening, autonomy + collaboration; - CASE approach (Corroborate + About Me + Science + Explain/Advise) for serious concerns; - Storytelling + personal experiences; - Address specific concerns with evidence; - Affirm parental love + caring; - Avoid shaming;

(3) Specific autism + MMR: - Wakefield 1998 fraudulent + retracted; - Over 1 million children studied across multiple meta-analyses — NO link; - Madsen, Hviid, others; - Real risks of measles (encephalitis, SSPE, death); recent outbreaks tragic;

(4) Vaccine schedule rationale: - Each vaccine added based on disease burden + safety; - Combined / multiple at once safe + effective; - Delay = vulnerable window; - 'Alternative schedules' not evidence-based; - Catch-up if behind;

(5) Vaccine adverse events: - VAERS surveillance system; - VICP (Vaccine Injury Compensation Program) — no-fault compensation; - Risk-benefit favors vaccination;

(6) State + school requirements: - School entry; - Religious + medical exemptions (variable by state); - Recent legislation tightening exemptions in some states (California SB 277);

(7) Resources for parents: CDC vaccine info, AAP HealthyChildren.org, Children's Hospital of Philadelphia Vaccine Education Center, Voices for Vaccines;

(8) Continuing the relationship: - Don't fire vaccine-hesitant families (controversial but recommended); - Continue to recommend each visit; - Build trust over time; - Document discussions + refusal forms;

(9) Disease re-emergence: measles in US (declared eliminated 2000) recurring with under-vaccination; pertussis outbreaks; recent vaccine-preventable deaths preventable;

(10) Provider self-care: hesitancy + refusal frustrating; institutional support;

(11) Public health response: outbreak vaccination, contact investigation, community education;

(12) Multidisciplinary: PCP + pediatric specialty + public health + community + school + media
————————————————
Vaccine hesitancy: presumptive recommendation; MI for hesitant; address concerns with evidence (MMR-autism DISPROVEN); CASE approach. Continue relationship + document. Resources. Real disease risks (measles re-emergence). State/school requirements. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Rectal Bleeding (BRBPR) Workup (AGA + ACG):

(1) History: characterize bleeding (with/separate from stool, amount, color), associated (pain, itching, discharge, mass, change in bowel habits, weight loss, family history CRC, IBD, smoking, NSAIDs);

(2) Exam: general, abdominal, rectal (inspection + DRE — fissures, hemorrhoids, masses, sphincter tone); anoscopy (in office) for direct visualization;

(3) Causes BRBPR: - Hemorrhoids — most common (internal painless, external painful if thrombosed); - Anal fissure — painful (tearing pain during BM, sentinel tag posterior most common, anterior may indicate trauma/Crohn's); - Polyps — usually painless; - Diverticular bleeding (typically intermittent, painless, larger volume); - Colitis (IBD, ischemic, infectious, radiation); - Colorectal cancer (must rule out — esp older, anemia, weight loss); - Anorectal trauma (sexual, foreign body, instrumentation); - Proctitis (radiation, STI, IBD); - Angiodysplasia (typically right colon, painless); - Solitary rectal ulcer;

(4) Colonoscopy indications (definitive): - Age ≥ 40-45 with rectal bleeding (lower threshold age 40 emerging); - Age < 40: if persistent / recurrent, red flags (anemia, weight loss, family history, change in bowel habits), uncertain source — colonoscopy; if low risk + clear hemorrhoidal cause + responds to treatment → conservative + repeat eval if persistent; - Anemia present; - Suspicion of malignancy; - This patient at age 50 — colonoscopy indicated;

(5) Hemorrhoid management: - Conservative: high-fiber diet + adequate fluid + sitz baths + topical (hydrocortisone, lidocaine); avoid straining + prolonged toilet; address constipation; - Office procedures: rubber band ligation (most effective), sclerotherapy, infrared coagulation; - Surgery (hemorrhoidectomy) for severe / Grade IV / refractory; - Thrombosed external — excision within 48-72 h if very painful; otherwise conservative;

(6) Anal fissure management: - Acute — sitz bath + bulk laxative + topical analgesic; usually heal; - Chronic — topical nitroglycerin / diltiazem / nifedipine; botox; sphincterotomy if refractory;

(7) STI proctitis screening for receptive anal sex + risk factors — NAAT chlamydia/gonorrhea + syphilis + HSV + HIV; treat per CDC;

(8) IBD considerations: if persistent, systemic symptoms, atypical features → endoscopy + biopsy + workup;

(9) CRC age 45 screening start USPSTF; this is opportunity for screening colonoscopy now;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + GI + colorectal surgery + dermatology selected + STI clinic if indicated
————————————————
Rectal bleeding: characterize + DRE + anoscopy. Causes (hemorrhoid common, but rule out malignancy especially ≥ 45 yo). Colonoscopy threshold low (age ≥ 40-45 or red flags). Hemorrhoid + fissure conservative + procedures + surgery if refractory. STI proctitis screening. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Comprehensive 6-Week Postpartum Visit (ACOG 2018 + AAFP):

(1) ACOG 2018 update — postpartum care as ongoing process not single visit — 'The 4th trimester' framework: - Initial contact (in-person or phone) within 3 wk; - Comprehensive postpartum visit by 12 wk (not just 6); - Tailored to needs; - Many specific issues (chronic disease management, lactation, mental health, family planning) address ongoing;

(2) Comprehensive assessment domains: - Mental health: PPD (EPDS, PHQ-9), anxiety, PTSD (especially traumatic birth, NICU baby, prior trauma), postpartum psychosis (rare, emergency), substance use, intimate partner violence screen; - Reproductive health: contraception, fertility, sexual function, dyspareunia, return of menses; - Lactation: support, problems, weaning decisions, medications during breastfeeding (LactMed); - Physical recovery: perineal/cesarean healing, urinary + fecal continence, prolapse, diastasis recti, pelvic pain; - Chronic conditions: BP (preeclampsia surveillance + future CV risk awareness — Hypertensive Disorders of Pregnancy = lifetime CV risk factor), diabetes (postpartum OGTT for GDM, T2DM monitoring), thyroid; - Nutrition + activity + sleep; - Social + family: childcare, return to work + workplace pumping rights (ACA), partner relationship, support system, financial; - Health behaviors: smoking, alcohol, substance use; - Vaccination update: Tdap if not in pregnancy, MMR if not immune (post-pregnancy as live), HepB, HPV catch-up, COVID, flu;

(3) Contraception counseling: - LARC (IUD, implant) most effective; - CDC US MEC: < 21 d avoid combined hormonal (VTE); progestin OK; transition combined OK 21-42 d if no risk; - Tubal ligation, vasectomy options; - Breastfeeding considerations (LAM limited, progestin compatible); - Pregnancy spacing recommendation 18-24 mo;

(4) Cardiovascular risk for women with pregnancy complications: - Preeclampsia, GDM, preterm birth, IUGR — all increase future CV risk; - Comprehensive CV risk assessment + lifestyle counseling; - Early ASCVD risk attention;

(5) Pelvic floor: - Pelvic floor physical therapy — first-line for incontinence + prolapse + dyspareunia + pelvic pain — underutilized despite strong evidence; - Surgical options later if refractory;

(6) Return-to-activity counseling: - Gradual exercise; - Sexual activity when ready (typically 4-6 wk if vaginal delivery uncomplicated); - Lifting, work return;

(7) Pediatric coordination: well-baby care + maternal-infant dyad;

(8) Father / partner mental health: paternal postpartum depression real — screen + treat;

(9) Future pregnancy planning: interconception care;

(10) Postpartum-specific support: groups, doulas, parenting classes;

(11) Multidisciplinary: family medicine well-positioned + OB + pediatrics + behavioral health + lactation consultant + pelvic floor PT + nutrition + social work + family
————————————————
Postpartum care: '4th trimester' ongoing not single visit (ACOG 2018). Comprehensive — mental health (PPD/anxiety), reproductive/contraception, lactation, physical recovery, chronic conditions (BP/DM as CV risk markers), pelvic floor PT. Father screening. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Hyponatremia Workup + Management Primary Care:

(1) Severity: mild (Na 130-134), moderate (125-129), severe (< 125); symptoms guide urgency (confusion, seizure, coma);

(2) Volume status assessment key: - Hypovolemic — diuretics, GI loss, third spacing, adrenal insufficiency; - Euvolemic (this patient) — SIADH most common cause (drugs — SSRI, carbamazepine, opioids, antipsychotics; lung — TB, pneumonia, small cell CA; CNS — stroke, infection, mass; surgery; postoperative; nausea; pain; idiopathic), hypothyroidism, adrenal insufficiency, primary polydipsia, beer potomania, low solute intake; - Hypervolemic — HF, cirrhosis, nephrotic syndrome, CKD;

(3) Workup: - Serum osmolality (rule out pseudo / translocational): - Hypotonic (true hyponatremia, < 280): most cases; - Iso/hypertonic: hyperglycemia, mannitol, contrast, pseudohyponatremia (hypertriglyceridemia, paraproteinemia); - Urine osmolality (~ free water excretion ability): - Low (< 100) — primary polydipsia, beer potomania, low solute; - High (> 100) — ADH active — SIADH, hypovolemia, hypervolemia; - Urine Na: < 20 (hypovolemia, hypervolemia); > 40 (SIADH, diuretic, adrenal/thyroid); - TSH + cortisol (rule out treatable endocrine); - BUN, Cr, glucose;

(4) SIADH diagnosis: euvolemic, hypotonic hyponatremia, urine osm > 100 (inappropriate concentration), urine Na > 30, normal kidney + adrenal + thyroid, no diuretic use;

(5) Treatment principles — careful correction (RAPID correction → osmotic demyelination syndrome (ODS) — irreversible neuro damage, esp in chronic hyponatremia, malnutrition, hypokalemia, alcoholism, liver disease): - Severe / symptomatic (seizure, coma) acute: 3% saline 100 mL bolus IV may repeat; ICU; raise Na 4-6 mmol/L acutely; - Maximum correction: 8-10 mmol/L per 24 h, 18 mmol/L per 48 h (some say 6-8/24 h chronic, > 6 wk; lower in high-risk); - Mild-moderate chronic asymptomatic: address underlying cause; - SIADH treatment: - Fluid restriction (800-1200 mL/d) first-line; - Salt + protein intake (urea); - Loop diuretic + Na supplementation; - Vaptans (tolvaptan — V2 receptor antagonist) for refractory; cost + hepatotoxicity caution; - Demeclocycline alternative; - Discontinue offending drugs;

(6) Drug discontinuation review: SSRIs, thiazides, NSAIDs, opioids, carbamazepine, antipsychotics, MDMA;

(7) Address underlying cause: hypothyroid → replace; adrenal insufficiency → steroid; SIADH cause (infection, cancer, CNS);

(8) Outpatient follow-up close: recheck Na in 24-48 h initial then weekly;

(9) Hospitalization for severe / symptomatic / unable to correct outpatient / unstable;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + nephrology + endocrine if SIADH workup + ED if severe
————————————————
Hyponatremia: volume + serum/urine osm + urine Na for diagnosis. SIADH common (drugs — SSRI; CNS; lung; postop). Careful correction to avoid ODS — max 8-10 mmol/L/24 h. Treat underlying + offending drugs. Severe → hypertonic saline ICU. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Immunocompromised Primary Care + Immunology Basics:

(1) Major types immunodeficiency: - Primary immunodeficiency (PID) — genetic (CVID, X-linked agammaglobulinemia, severe combined ID, complement deficiencies, hyper-IgM, Wiskott-Aldrich, ataxia-telangiectasia, chronic granulomatous disease, etc.); often detected childhood; - Secondary / acquired: - HIV; - Malignancy (especially hematologic — lymphoma, leukemia, myeloma); - Chemotherapy + targeted therapy (CD20 — rituximab; BTK; checkpoint inhibitors); - Immunosuppressants (steroids, calcineurin inhibitors, MMF, azathioprine, methotrexate, biologics — TNF, IL-6, IL-17, IL-23, B-cell, T-cell, JAK inhibitors); - Transplant (solid organ + HSCT); - Diabetes + uncontrolled hyperglycemia; - Splenectomy / asplenia (functional — sickle cell); - Malnutrition; - CKD / ESRD; - Cirrhosis; - Aging (immunosenescence); - Pregnancy (mild physiologic immunosuppression);

(2) Workup suspected: - Recurrent / unusual / severe infections; - Family history; - Quantitative immunoglobulins (IgG, IgA, IgM, IgE); - Lymphocyte subsets (CD3, CD4, CD8, CD19, CD56); - Vaccine response (T-cell-independent — Pneumovax; T-cell-dependent — tetanus); - Complement (CH50, C3, C4); - HIV; - Refer immunology specialist;

(3) Vaccinations in immunocompromised: - Generally AVOID live vaccines: MMR, varicella, yellow fever, oral typhoid, BCG, oral polio, smallpox (limited situations); - Recombinant Shingrix preferred over live Zostavax in immunocompromised — ACIP recommends ≥ 19 yo immunocompromised; - Inactivated vaccines safe but may have reduced response: - More doses or higher doses often (e.g., 4 doses HepB 40 mcg dialysis); - Pneumococcal: PCV20 or PCV15 + PPSV23 8 wk apart (vs 1 yr) for immunocompromised; - Vaccinate before immunosuppression when possible: 2-4 wk live vaccines, 2 wk inactivated; - HSCT recipients: revaccination protocols (lose immune memory); - Solid organ transplant: optimize before transplant; live vaccines avoided lifelong after; - Biologics specific: - Anti-CD20 (rituximab) — vaccinate ≥ 4 wk before; reduced response × 6 mo after; - Anti-TNF — reduced response; reasonable to vaccinate while on; - Steroid: > 20 mg prednisone × 2 wk = immunosuppressed;

(4) Infection prevention + prophylaxis: - PCP (Pneumocystis jirovecii) prophylaxis: TMP-SMX for HIV (CD4 < 200), post-transplant, certain chemo regimens, ANCA vasculitis, others; - CMV prophylaxis: post-transplant + selected; - Fungal prophylaxis: selected high-risk; - Toxoplasmosis for HIV (CD4 < 100); - Hand hygiene + masking + avoidance crowds + sick contacts; - Food safety + water + travel precautions; - Pet safety education (toxoplasmosis, salmonella); - Wound care prompt; - Dental care good hygiene;

(5) Recognition of infections: - May present atypically (less fever, less inflammation); - Lower threshold for evaluation + treatment; - Broad differentials (opportunistic + community); - Cultures + biopsies; - Empiric treatment broader;

(6) Specific situations: - Asplenia: vaccinate (encapsulated — pneumococcal, Hib, meningococcal ACWY + B), prophylactic antibiotic for some, medical alert ID, prompt evaluation fever + early empiric ceftriaxone; - Sickle cell: similar + penicillin prophylaxis childhood; - Neutropenic fever: emergency; - HIV + low CD4: opportunistic infection screening + prophylaxis; ART initiation;

(7) Cancer surveillance: immunocompromised at increased risk for several cancers — screening per protocols + appropriate;

(8) Mental health + caregiver support;

(9) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ID + immunology + transplant + oncology + relevant specialists + pharmacy + nursing + nutrition + behavioral health
————————————————
Immunocompromised: types (primary + secondary). Workup if recurrent/unusual. Vaccines: avoid live, more doses, recombinant Shingrix preferred. Infection prevention + prophylaxis (PCP, CMV, etc.). Atypical presentations — low threshold. Asplenia considerations. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Nutrition Science + Dietary Patterns Primary Care (AAFP + Dietary Guidelines 2020-2025):

(1) Dietary Patterns Approach (vs single nutrient) increasingly emphasized — DGA 2020-2025: - Mediterranean — strongest evidence CV, metabolic, cognitive, mortality (PREDIMED); plant-predominant, olive oil, fish, nuts, whole grains, moderate wine; - DASH — CV, BP (DASH-Sodium); similar to Mediterranean; - Plant-based — vegetarian / vegan / flexitarian; growing evidence; - Healthy US-style (DGA); - Low-carb / Mediterranean-low-carb / ketogenic — short-term weight + metabolic benefit; long-term data more limited; - Intermittent fasting — emerging; mixed evidence; - Whole food, minimally processed common theme — avoid ultra-processed (NOVA classification);

(2) Macronutrients (DGA 2020-2025): - Carbohydrate: 45-65% — whole grains, fiber, complex; limit added sugar (< 10% calories); - Protein: 10-35% — plant + lean animal + fish; - Fat: 20-35% — unsaturated (mono + poly — olive, avocado, nuts, fish); limit saturated (< 10% calories — red meat, full-fat dairy, butter); avoid trans (essentially banned); - Fiber: 25-38 g/d (most Americans < 50%); - Hydration: ~ 2-3 L/d total;

(3) Specific nutrient considerations: - Sodium: < 2300 mg/d (< 1500 high BP) — most Americans 3500+; - Calcium + vit D: bone + cancer protection; primarily food; supplements selective; - Iron: bioavailability heme > non-heme; pair with vit C; - B12: animal sources; supplement vegetarians + > 50 yo; - Folate: leafy green + fortified; pregnancy 400-800 mcg; - Omega-3 (EPA + DHA): fatty fish 2x/wk; ALA plant sources lower conversion; supplements selected; - Iodine: salt fortified, seafood; - Vit B-complex, antioxidants, magnesium, potassium, zinc — food preferred;

(4) Special populations: - Pregnancy + lactation: increased needs, folate, iron, DHA, calcium, vit D, choline; avoid alcohol, high mercury fish, raw, listeria-risk; - Infants: breast / formula + introduction solid 6 mo + iron-fortified + allergens early; - Children + adolescents: growth + development; calcium + vit D; limit added sugar / sugar-sweetened beverages; - Older adults: protein needs increase (1-1.2 g/kg); B12; vit D; calcium; address chewing + swallowing + appetite + social; - Athletes: macros + hydration + timing; - Chronic disease specific: - DM: carbohydrate management, glycemic index, Mediterranean / DASH; - CKD: protein moderate, K + phos as advances; - CV: Mediterranean + DASH; - HF: Na restriction + fluid; - Cancer: support during treatment; survivorship; - Liver disease: branched-chain amino acids, sodium; - GI: low-FODMAP for IBS, gluten-free celiac, low-residue acute IBD;

(5) Weight management: - Modest calorie deficit; - Quality of diet > calories alone; - Behavioral + structured programs; - Intermittent fasting options; - Very low calorie diets for severe; - Bariatric for severe + comorbidity;

(6) Common myths + misconceptions: - 'Dietary cholesterol' less important than once thought (DGA 2015 removed limit); - 'Eat fat to lose fat' qualified; - Detoxes + cleanses not evidence-based; - Supplements for healthy people limited benefit; - Sugar — not single villain but context; - Ultra-processed food epidemiologic concern; - Food allergies vs intolerances vs gluten sensitivity differ;

(7) Food insecurity screening + intervention: critical SDOH;

(8) Food + medication interactions: warfarin + vit K, MAOI + tyramine, grapefruit + meds;

(9) Cultural considerations + personalization;

(10) Nutrition counseling: brief in primary care; refer dietitian / RDN for comprehensive; Medicare benefit DM, CKD;

(11) Lifestyle medicine integration;

(12) Multidisciplinary: PCP + RDN/dietitian + diabetes educator + behavioral health + community programs + SDOH resources
————————————————
Nutrition: dietary patterns > single nutrient. Mediterranean strongest evidence (PREDIMED). DASH, plant-based, healthy US-style. Macros + key nutrients. Special populations + chronic disease specific. Address food insecurity. RDN for comprehensive. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Physical Activity Prescription + Exercise as Medicine (CDC + ACSM + DGA):

(1) Major impact: physical activity = one of most impactful interventions for prevention + treatment of chronic disease, mental health, mortality;

(2) CDC + DGA 2018 Physical Activity Guidelines: - Adults: - 150 min/wk moderate (brisk walking) OR 75 min/wk vigorous (jogging) OR combination; - Plus muscle-strengthening ≥ 2 d/wk (all major muscle groups); - More benefit with more — up to 300 min/wk; - Move more, sit less (sedentary behavior independent risk); - Older adults: above + balance training; modify per ability; - Children + adolescents: 60 min/d moderate-vigorous + muscle/bone strengthening 3x/wk; - Pregnancy + postpartum: 150 min/wk moderate; modify per stage; - Chronic conditions: still strongly recommended with adaptations;

(3) Exercise prescription components (FITT): - Frequency; - Intensity (talk test, HR zones, RPE); - Time (duration); - Type (aerobic, resistance, flexibility, balance);

(4) Intensity gauges: - Moderate: increased HR + breathing + sweat; can talk but not sing; ~ 50-70% HRmax; - Vigorous: significantly increased; only few words; ~ 70-85% HRmax; - Maximum HR: 220 - age (rough); - MET-min/wk > 500 = adequate;

(5) Exercise as therapy — specific evidence: - Cardiovascular disease: cardiac rehab, prevention, post-event; - Hypertension: 5-10 mmHg BP reduction; - T2DM + prediabetes: improved insulin sensitivity, A1c reduction; DPP includes; - Dyslipidemia: HDL + TG improvement; - Obesity: weight + body composition + maintenance; - Cancer: prevention multiple cancers, during/after treatment improvement (fatigue, QOL, recurrence reduction breast/colon); - Mental health: depression (effective as antidepressants for mild-moderate), anxiety, cognition, dementia prevention; - Osteoporosis: weight-bearing + resistance for bone; - Osteoarthritis: paradoxically beneficial — exercise = first-line; - COPD: pulmonary rehab; - HF: cardiac rehab + exercise training; - PAD: structured exercise > revascularization for claudication (CLEVER); - Stroke recovery: rehab + ongoing; - Falls prevention: tai chi, multimodal; - Sleep: improves; - Mortality: dose-response — even small amounts reduce;

(6) Pre-exercise screening: ACSM updated — most healthy adults can begin without medical clearance; clearance for: known disease + symptoms + advanced age + intense activity;

(7) Specific populations: - Cardiac rehab Class I post-MI, stable angina, HF, post-CABG/PCI/valve, PAD; - Pulmonary rehab for COPD + ILD + others; - Cancer rehab survivorship; - Vestibular rehab; - Pelvic floor PT; - Vestibular + balance; - Children with disability;

(8) Behavior change principles (see separate): motivational interviewing, goal-setting, environmental, social, technology;

(9) Address barriers: time, access, safety, weather, mobility, knowledge, motivation, cost, social;

(10) Technology: wearables (Fitbit, Apple Watch, Garmin), apps, virtual programs, exergaming, gamification;

(11) Group + community programs: SilverSneakers (Medicare), local gyms, parks + recreation, walking groups, faith-based;

(12) Provider counseling effective: brief counseling + prescription + referral; Exercise is Medicine initiative;

(13) Multidisciplinary: PCP + exercise physiologist + PT + cardiac/pulm rehab + community programs + occupational therapy + behavioral health
————————————————
Physical activity: 150 min/wk mod + strength 2x/wk adults (DGA). Less sedentary. FITT prescription. Therapy for nearly all chronic conditions (CV, DM, mental health, cancer, OA, etc.). Most adults can start without clearance. Cardiac/pulm rehab. Behavior change + tech + community. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Sleep Medicine Basics + Primary Care (AASM):

(1) Sleep architecture: ~ 90 min cycles; NREM (N1, N2, N3 — deep) + REM (dreaming, memory consolidation); 4-6 cycles/night;

(2) Sleep duration recommendations (NSF + AAP): - Newborn 0-3 mo: 14-17 h; - Infant 4-11 mo: 12-15 h; - Toddler 1-2 yr: 11-14 h; - Preschool 3-5 yr: 10-13 h; - School age 6-13 yr: 9-11 h; - Teen 14-17 yr: 8-10 h (often inadequate — early school start times, screens); - Adult 18-64: 7-9 h; - Older adult ≥ 65: 7-8 h;

(3) Sleep deprivation effects: - Acute: cognition, mood, immune, metabolic; - Chronic (< 7 h adult): increased mortality, CV disease, DM, obesity, mental health, accidents (drowsy driving = drunk driving), cancer (shift work IARC group 2A);

(4) Sleep hygiene — foundation: - Regular schedule (even weekends); - Dark, cool, quiet bedroom (60-67°F); - Bed for sleep + sex only; - Avoid screens 1+ h before bed (blue light); - Caffeine cutoff afternoon; - Alcohol disrupts; - Exercise (not late); - Limit naps (< 30 min, early); - Sunlight exposure morning; - Relaxation routine; - Manage stress;

(5) Major sleep disorders primary care: - Insomnia disorder — see separate (CBT-I first-line); - OSA — see separate (CPAP + lifestyle + GLP-1 emerging); - Central sleep apnea — HF, opioid, idiopathic; - Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS) / Willis-Ekbom: urge to move + dysesthesia + evening + relief with movement; Workup: ferritin (target > 75-100, supplement), Cr, glucose, thyroid; Treatment: iron repletion if low; alpha-2-delta ligands (gabapentin, pregabalin — first-line shift); dopamine agonists (pramipexole, ropinirole — augmentation issue, less preferred now); rotigotine patch; opioids low-dose refractory; - Narcolepsy: excessive daytime sleepiness + cataplexy (type 1) + sleep paralysis + hypnagogic hallucinations; polysomnography + MSLT; modafinil/armodafinil, sodium oxybate, pitolisant, solriamfetol; refer sleep medicine; - Circadian rhythm disorders: delayed/advanced sleep phase, shift work, jet lag, irregular; melatonin + light therapy + chronotherapy; - Parasomnias: sleepwalking, night terrors, REM behavior disorder (alpha-synucleinopathy risk — Parkinson, DLB, MSA progression); - Hypersomnia disorders: idiopathic, Kleine-Levin; - Bruxism: dental + stress; - Sleep-related movement disorders: PLMS;

(6) Pediatric sleep: - Sleep training (multiple methods debated); - SIDS prevention (back to sleep, firm surface, no co-sleeping same bed, no soft objects); - OSA in children — adenotonsillectomy first-line; - ADHD + sleep bidirectional; - Adolescent later chronotype + school start times advocacy;

(7) Pregnancy + postpartum: sleep changes; RLS common; OSA can develop; preeclampsia association;

(8) Mental health bidirectional: depression, anxiety, PTSD, bipolar — sleep disruption + treatment;

(9) Substance use + sleep: stimulants, alcohol, opioids, marijuana — affect sleep;

(10) Sleep + cognitive aging: deep sleep + glymphatic clearance + dementia prevention emerging evidence;

(11) Drowsy driving + occupational safety; commercial drivers OSA screening;

(12) Sleep tracking technology: wearables increasingly accurate; orthosomnia (anxiety from data);

(13) Multidisciplinary: PCP + sleep medicine + ENT (OSA pediatric) + dental sleep (oral appliance) + behavioral health (CBT-I) + neurology + cardiology
————————————————
Sleep: 7-9 h adult; sleep hygiene foundation. Major disorders — insomnia (CBT-I), OSA (CPAP), RLS (iron + gabapentinoid), narcolepsy (sleep med referral), parasomnias. Pediatric considerations. Pregnancy + mental health bidirectional. Drowsy driving + tech. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Pediatric Development + Screening Primary Care (AAP Bright Futures):

(1) Developmental domains: - Motor (gross + fine); - Language (receptive + expressive); - Cognitive; - Social-emotional; - Adaptive / self-help;

(2) Surveillance vs screening: - Surveillance: ongoing process at every visit — history, parent concerns, observation; - Screening: standardized tool at specific intervals;

(3) Recommended screening intervals (AAP): - General developmental (ASQ, PEDS): 9, 18, 30 mo; - Autism-specific (M-CHAT-R/F): 18 + 24 mo; - Maternal depression: 1, 2, 4, 6 mo; - Lead: targeted; many recommend universal Medicaid; - Anemia: 9-12 mo; - TB: targeted; - Lipid: 9-11 + 17-21 yo; - HIV: 13+ yo; - Behavioral: at all WCV (PSC, CBCL); - Adolescent depression (PHQ-A): annually 12+ yo;

(4) Key milestones (AAP 2022 updated): - 2 mo: social smile, coo, lift head prone; - 4 mo: laugh, roll, reach; - 6 mo: sit support, babble, transfer; - 9 mo: pincer grasp, mama/dada, wave bye, separation anxiety; - 12 mo: walk, 1-2 words, pat-a-cake; - 15 mo: 3-5 words, point to wants; - 18 mo: 10+ words, 1-step commands, run, scribble, parallel play; - 24 mo: 2-word phrases, run + kick ball, points to body parts; - 3 yr: 3-word sentences, draw circle, tricycle, dress with help; - 4 yr: count to 10, draw person, hop, dress self; - 5 yr: print name, skip, count to 20, friend relationships;

(5) Red flags requiring evaluation: - No social smile by 3 mo; - Cannot hold head up by 4 mo; - No babbling by 9 mo; - No words by 16 mo; - No 2-word phrases by 24 mo; - Loss of skills any age (regression); - Lack of social interest / engagement; - No pointing by 18 mo; - No interactive play; - Hand preference < 18 mo (could indicate hemiparesis);

(6) Common conditions screening detects: - Autism spectrum disorder (1 in 36 — CDC); - Speech-language delay; - Intellectual disability; - ADHD (older); - Learning disability; - Hearing loss; - Vision impairment; - Cerebral palsy + motor disorders;

(7) Early intervention referral don't delay: - Part C (IDEA — birth to 3) — Early Intervention free; - Part B (IDEA — 3-21) — school-based services; IEP; 504 plan; - Concurrent referrals — audiology, vision, specialty; - Family training + support;

(8) Vision + hearing: - Newborn hearing screen mandatory most states; - Vision screening at WCV per AAP + AAO; - Photoscreener instrument-based 3+ yo; - Refer ophthalmology if positive or risk;

(9) Other screening: - Newborn metabolic + endocrine screening (state panels); - CCHD screening newborn (critical congenital heart); - Hip dysplasia (Barlow + Ortolani + Galeazzi infancy); - Scoliosis adolescent;

(10) Family-centered communication: parents are partners; reassure normalcy + concerning findings; cultural humility;

(11) Special situations: prematurity (corrected age), adoption, foster, history of risk;

(12) Anticipatory guidance at each visit per Bright Futures;

(13) Multidisciplinary: PCP + EI team + audiology + ophthalmology + speech-language + OT + PT + developmental pediatrics + autism specialist + school + family
————————————————
Pediatric development: surveillance every visit + screening (ASQ 9/18/30 mo, M-CHAT-R/F 18+24 mo). Key milestones knowledge. Red flags → don't delay EI referral. Audiology + vision + other screens. Family-centered. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Medications in Pregnancy + Lactation (FDA PLLR + LactMed + ACOG):

(1) FDA Pregnancy + Lactation Labeling Rule (PLLR) — 2015 replaced old A/B/C/D/X categories: - Pregnancy summary with risk; - Lactation summary; - Females + males of reproductive potential; - More nuanced + evidence-based; categories abandoned;

(2) Key principles: - No medication completely safe in pregnancy/lactation; - No medication automatically contraindicated — assess benefit vs risk to mother + fetus/infant; - Untreated condition often greater risk than medication (e.g., depression, asthma, epilepsy, HIV); - Trimester matters: 1st (organogenesis 2-8 wk PCD), 2nd, 3rd, near delivery, postpartum; - Lowest effective dose + duration; - Preferred agents within class when alternatives; - Counsel + document shared decision; - Resources: LactMed (free NIH), TERIS, Reprotox, MotherToBaby, ACOG/specialty guidelines;

(3) Common medications + pregnancy: - Antibiotics: penicillins / cephalosporins / azithromycin generally safe; AVOID — tetracyclines (after 1st trimester — bones + teeth), fluoroquinolones (cartilage, FDA caution though emerging more nuanced), aminoglycosides (ototoxic), TMP-SMX (1st trim — folate antagonist; 3rd trim — kernicterus, neonatal hyperbilirubinemia); nitrofurantoin avoid 38+ wk (hemolytic anemia neonatal G6PD); - Hypertension: methyldopa, labetalol, nifedipine OK; AVOID — ACE/ARB (renal + skull anomalies 2nd-3rd trim), atenolol (IUGR); - DM: insulin preferred; metformin (acceptable per ACOG); glyburide (decreased use — neonatal hypoglycemia); - Anticoagulation: heparin / LMWH preferred (no placental transfer); warfarin teratogen (esp 1st trim); DOACs limited data, avoid; - Anti-seizure: minimize teratogens; preferred — lamotrigine, levetiracetam; AVOID — valproic acid (highest teratogenicity NTD + cognitive); carbamazepine, phenytoin moderate; supplement folate 4 mg before + during pregnancy; - Antidepressants: SSRIs generally acceptable (sertraline preferred), paroxetine slight CV concern 1st trim (older data), avoid abrupt discontinuation; benefits often outweigh risks for moderate-severe depression; - NSAIDs: avoid 3rd trim (premature closure ductus arteriosus, oligohydramnios, kidney); 1st-2nd trim limited use OK; - Acetaminophen: generally safe but recent observational concerns ADHD/autism (causality not established); minimize unnecessary use; - Opioids: pregnancy MOUD (buprenorphine, methadone) for OUD better than detox; otherwise minimize; neonatal abstinence; - Vaccines: inactivated safe + recommended (Tdap, flu, COVID, RSV); avoid live (MMR, varicella, yellow fever — postpone if possible); - Imaging: minimize radiation, US + MRI safer; CT with shielding selected; iodinated contrast generally avoid; gadolinium avoid (especially 1st trim); - Anesthesia: regional preferred when possible;

(4) Common medications + lactation: - LactMed first-resource; - Generally safe: most antibiotics, common antihypertensives, SSRIs (sertraline, paroxetine — minimal milk transfer), low-dose opioids brief, insulin, levothyroxine, hydroxychloroquine, low-dose steroids; - Caution: pseudoephedrine (↓ milk supply), bromocriptine/cabergoline (suppress lactation), lithium (high transfer, monitor infant), warfarin OK; - Avoid: chemotherapy, radioactive iodine, ergot alkaloids;

(5) Periconception counseling: - Folate 400 mcg routine, 4 mg if prior NTD or AED use; - Review chronic medications + optimize teratogenic; - DM, BP, thyroid optimization; - Vaccinations update; - Lifestyle (smoking, alcohol, substance, weight, nutrition); - Genetic carrier screening;

(6) Special populations: - OUD pregnancy: MOUD preferred; - HIV: ART continued / initiated; - Epilepsy: minimize teratogens; - Mental illness: weigh untreated vs treatment risks; - Autoimmune: hydroxychloroquine OK; some biologics; - Chronic pain: minimize opioids; - Transplant: immunosuppression continued;

(7) Postpartum + lactation drug choices: minimize unnecessary; choose preferred; LactMed look-up;

(8) Father-to-be exposures + paternal effects: emerging consideration;

(9) Documentation: shared decisions, counseling, alternatives considered;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + OB + MFM + pharmacy + specialty (psych, ID, etc.) + neonatology + lactation
————————————————
Pregnancy + lactation pharm: PLLR (categories abandoned). Benefit-risk individualized. Untreated condition often worse. LactMed + resources. Common safe/avoid lists per condition. Periconception optimization. Special populations. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Preventive Medicine Principles (USPSTF + CDC + Healthy People 2030):

(1) Levels of prevention: - Primary — prevent disease occurrence (vaccination, lifestyle modification, smoking cessation, fluoride, seatbelts); - Secondary — early detection + treatment (screening — cancer, BP, glucose); - Tertiary — limit complications of existing disease (cardiac rehab, glycemic control to prevent complications); - Quaternary — protect from harms of medicine itself (avoid overtesting, overtreatment, overdiagnosis);

(2) USPSTF grades: - A strong recommendation high certainty net benefit; - B moderate certainty; - C small net benefit — individual decision; - D recommend against; - I insufficient evidence; - A + B routinely cover preventive services under ACA without cost-sharing;

(3) Key USPSTF preventive recommendations adults: - BP screening all adults ≥ 18; - Cholesterol screening age-based; - DM screening 35-70 + overweight; - Cancer screening: - Cervical 21-65; - Breast 40-74 biennial (USPSTF 2024 lowered to 40); - Colorectal 45-75 (lowered from 50); - Lung 50-80 with 20 pack-year history; - Prostate 55-69 shared decision; - Cervical, skin (selected), oral; - Osteoporosis women 65+ (younger if risk); - AAA men 65-75 ever-smoker; - Hepatitis C all adults 18-79; - Hepatitis B all adults (2023); - HIV 15-65; - Latent TB at-risk; - STIs risk-based; - Depression all adults including pregnant + postpartum; - Anxiety adults < 65 (USPSTF 2023); - Substance use alcohol + drugs + tobacco; - IPV women reproductive age; - Falls ≥ 65; - Lifestyle counseling weight, exercise, diet, smoking;

(4) Vaccinations per CDC schedule (see separate);

(5) Choosing Wisely / Quaternary prevention: avoid: - Unnecessary cancer screening (older, low risk, less benefit); - Routine imaging headache, LBP; - Routine EKG/CXR asymptomatic; - Annual physical detailed labs not evidence-based; - Antibiotic for viral; - PPI long-term without indication; - Polypharmacy without rationale; - Cancer screening with limited life expectancy;

(6) Shared decision-making essential for many — especially C-grade or where benefits/harms close;

(7) Risk assessment + stratification: Pooled Cohort Equations, FRAX, Tyrer-Cuzick, Lung CA risk, etc.;

(8) Counseling effective in primary care — even brief (e.g., smoking cessation 5 As, alcohol SBIRT);

(9) Population health + community level: water fluoridation, immunization programs, tobacco policy, food labeling, built environment, school health, workplace wellness;

(10) Health equity in prevention: stratify outcomes + address disparities;

(11) Healthy People 2030 framework: leading health indicators across domains;

(12) Implementation in practice: EHR reminders, team-based delivery, registries, outreach;

(13) Pediatric preventive (Bright Futures): - Vaccines per CDC; - Growth + development; - Lead, lipid, anemia, dental, vision/hearing screening; - Anticipatory guidance;

(14) Multidisciplinary: PCP + nursing + APP + behavioral health + dietitian + public health + community + school + workplace + family
————————————————
Prevention: 4 levels (primary, secondary, tertiary, quaternary — avoid overuse). USPSTF grades guide preventive services. Key recommendations adults. Counseling effective. Risk stratification. Community + policy levels. Equity. Implementation in practice. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Patient Safety + Just Culture (IHI + AHRQ + IOM):

(1) Magnitude: medical errors ~ 3rd leading cause of death US (Makary BMJ 2016 estimate ~ 250,000/yr); primary care + ambulatory errors common but less studied;

(2) IOM (now NAM) framework — 'To Err is Human' (1999) + 'Crossing the Quality Chasm' (2001): - System problem, not individual; - Build safer systems; - 6 aims: Safe + Effective + Patient-centered + Timely + Efficient + Equitable; - 'Quintuple Aim' adds clinician well-being + equity;

(3) Just culture: - Distinguish: - Human error (slip, lapse) → console + system fix; - At-risk behavior (taking shortcut) → coach; - Reckless behavior (knowing risk) → discipline; - Psychological safety — speak up about safety without fear; - Learning culture > blame culture; - Reduces underreporting + improves system improvement;

(4) High-Reliability Organization (HRO) principles (Weick + Sutcliffe): - Preoccupation with failure; - Reluctance to simplify; - Sensitivity to operations; - Commitment to resilience; - Deference to expertise;

(5) Common error categories primary care: - Diagnostic errors — missed, delayed, wrong (especially cancer, MI, stroke, infection, PE) — leading cause primary care malpractice; - Medication errors — prescribing, dispensing, monitoring, communication; - Communication failures: handoffs, results, between team; - Care coordination + referrals: lost referrals, missed results; - Test result management: missed abnormal results most common; - Documentation: unclear, illegible (less now), missing; - Follow-up failures; - Care transitions: hospital-to-home, between settings;

(6) System solutions: - Closed-loop communication: results → patient → action → documentation; - Robust safety net systems: EHR reminders, automated follow-up, recall systems, panel management; - Standardization + checklists: surgical safety, central line, OB, sepsis, NEW for primary care; - Decision support: EHR alerts, clinical pathways, decision aids; - Medication safety: e-prescribing, drug interaction checking, medication reconciliation, double-checks for high-risk; - Read-back + verification; - Adequate staffing + workload; - Fatigue + burnout reduction;

(7) Reporting + analysis: - Voluntary incident reporting (low-threshold, blame-free) + system feedback; - Root cause analysis (RCA) for serious events — identify system causes; - Failure modes + effects analysis (FMEA) prospective risk identification; - Mortality + morbidity conferences — learning oriented; - AHRQ Common Formats standardized;

(8) Disclosure of errors: - Ethical + legal (most jurisdictions); - CANDOR program — Communication and Optimal Resolution; - Empathic, honest, system focus; - Reduces litigation when done well; - Apology laws (varies);

(9) Patient engagement in safety: - Speak up programs; - Medication reconciliation involvement; - Question + understand care; - Patient + family advisory councils;

(10) Health literacy + plain language essential;

(11) Specific safety priorities WHO, AHRQ, Joint Commission goals: - Patient ID; - Communication of test results / handoffs; - Medication safety (high-alert); - Infection prevention; - Falls; - Surgical safety; - Suicide prevention; - DVT prophylaxis; - Sepsis recognition;

(12) Outpatient-specific safety: telephone advice protocols, after-hours coverage, cross-coverage, test results management, abnormal result tracking, no-show follow-up, controlled substances;

(13) Clinician well-being + safety: 2nd victim phenomenon (clinician trauma after adverse event); peer support, debriefing;

(14) Resources: IHI, AHRQ PSNet, Joint Commission, state QIOs, NPSF (now part of IHI);

(15) Multidisciplinary: clinicians + risk + quality + patients + administration + IT + nursing + pharmacy + legal + insurance
————————————————
Patient safety: system focus (IOM). Just culture (distinguish human error, at-risk, reckless). HRO principles. Common errors (diagnostic, medication, communication, results). System solutions (closed-loop, checklists, decision support). CANDOR disclosure. Patient engagement. Wellbeing — 2nd victim. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Specialty Referral Management Optimization:

(1) Referral problems: long wait times, inadequate information transfer (both directions), missed referrals, duplicated tests, lack of feedback, fragmented care, patient confusion;

(2) Structured referral processes: - Standardized templates with key clinical info; - Triage at receiving end to prioritize urgency; - Referral coordinators / hubs; - Two-way communication mandated; - Closing the loop: receipt confirmation, consult report back;

(3) eConsults / asynchronous specialty consultation: - PCP submits structured question + relevant data; - Specialist responds within days; - Avoids in-person visit ~ 50%+ for appropriate conditions; - Project ECHO model — telementoring + capacity building (Sanjeev Arora UNM); evidence in multiple conditions (HCV, chronic pain, opioid use); - Improves access esp underserved;

(4) Co-management + collaborative care: - Collaborative Care Model (mental health) — measurement-based + care manager + specialist consultation; - Cardio-renal-endocrine coordination; - Specialty-PCP shared chronic disease management (e.g., cardiology shared care HF, endocrine shared DM);

(5) Direct booking + scheduling tools: - Patient self-scheduling specialists with PCP referral approval; - Shared calendars; - Reduce gatekeeper burden;

(6) Network optimization: - Narrow networks with quality + cost focus; - Centers of excellence for complex; - Direct contracting;

(7) Information exchange: - EHR same system (Epic, Cerner) — facilitates; - HIEs (Health Information Exchanges) across systems; - FHIR + interoperability standards; - Structured + complete referral data + consult notes;

(8) Quality metrics: - Time to specialist appointment; - Information transfer completeness both directions; - Follow-up completion; - Patient experience with referral process; - Avoidable specialty visits (could have been handled in primary care with support);

(9) Patient experience improvements: - Transparent process + expectations; - Pre-referral education; - Logistics support (transportation, scheduling, navigation); - Post-referral follow-up;

(10) Capacity building primary care: - Specialist mentoring (ECHO model); - Continuing education; - Clinical decision support; - In-clinic specialty support (visiting specialist, mini-residencies); - Practice transformation; - More primary care can manage = less referral needed;

(11) Specific high-volume referral pathways: - Cardiology, GI, dermatology, orthopedics, psychiatry — most common; - Standardized pathways; - Pre-referral workup expectations;

(12) Equity in specialty access: - Insurance + cost barriers; - Geographic / transportation; - Language access; - Cultural fit; - Closing referral gap for underserved;

(13) Workforce considerations: - Specialty + primary care workforce alignment; - Mid-level provider integration; - Telemedicine expansion;

(14) Cost considerations: - Avoid unnecessary specialty visits + duplicative testing; - Specialty cost + value variation;

(15) Multidisciplinary: PCP + specialists + care coordinators + referral coordinators + IT + administration + quality + patients + insurance + community partners
————————————————
Specialty referral: structured + close the loop. eConsults + ECHO + co-management. Direct booking. Information exchange. Quality metrics. Patient experience. Capacity building primary care. Equity. Workforce. Cost. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Telemedicine in Primary Care — Best Practices (ATA + AAFP):

(1) Modalities: - Synchronous video: real-time, most like in-person; - Synchronous audio: telephone only; - Asynchronous (store + forward): patient submits photo/info; - Remote patient monitoring (RPM): BP, glucose, weight, SpO2, ECG, wearables; - eVisits: messaging-based; - eConsults: provider-to-provider (see separate);

(2) Appropriate use cases: - Routine chronic disease follow-up (HTN, DM, lipid); - Behavioral health (depression, anxiety, substance use, therapy); - Medication management + refills; - Minor acute conditions (URI, skin rashes, UTI selected); - Follow-up after labs/imaging; - Lifestyle counseling; - Care management + coordination; - Pre + post-procedural; - Specialty consultations; - Post-acute / hospital follow-up; - Rural + access-limited;

(3) Not appropriate: - Acute serious conditions needing physical exam; - Procedures; - Imaging-required diagnoses; - When physical exam essential; - Some sensitive issues (preferences vary); - Technology / language barriers severe;

(4) Best practices visit conduct: - Pre-visit: technology check, privacy/HIPAA, intake forms, consent; - Setting: quiet, well-lit, eye-level camera, professional appearance; - Introduction: identify self + confirm patient identity + setting privacy + explain technology; - Webside manner: eye contact (look at camera), unhurried, attentive, address technology issues; - Limited physical exam adapted: visual inspection, patient-performed maneuvers (palpation, ROM), home BP/wt/temp, smartphone tools; - Documentation: telemedicine modality + duration + key findings; - Follow-up + close the loop;

(5) Technology considerations: - Platforms: Epic MyChart Video, Doxy.me, Zoom for Healthcare, others; HIPAA-compliant; - Patient access: smartphone, tablet, computer; broadband; - Alternatives for digital divide: telephone, in-person; - Backup plan for technical issues; - Patient portal integration;

(6) Regulatory + reimbursement: - Post-PHE COVID landscape evolving — pre-PHE many restrictions removed; - Audio-only parity in many states (varies); - Interstate licensure — Interstate Medical Licensure Compact + state-specific telehealth licensure; - Controlled substance prescribing — DEA rules evolving post-PHE (Ryan Haight Act + extensions); - Reimbursement parity — Medicare + Medicaid + commercial; varies; - Originating site restrictions historically (many waived);

(7) Quality + safety considerations: - Safe vs in-person? — emerging evidence comparable many conditions; - Triage carefully — when to convert to in-person; - Care transitions to in-person when needed; - No-show + access disparities; - Outcomes monitoring;

(8) Health equity: - Digital divide — broadband, devices, digital literacy, language; - Provide alternatives (audio, community-based, in-person); - Support resources: community Wi-Fi, lending programs, low-cost broadband (FCC ACP);

(9) Special populations: - Pediatric: parent involvement; specific considerations (developmental, parental support); - Geriatric: technology support; in-home help; - Mental health: very effective + accessible; specific platforms; - Underserved + rural: significant benefit + access; - Disabilities: accessibility (captions, sign language interpreter); - Limited English: video interpreters;

(10) Practice integration: - Workflow design: scheduling, intake, visit, follow-up, billing; - Hybrid practice: balance + flexibility; - Staff training; - Patient education + materials; - Quality improvement ongoing;

(11) Provider considerations: - Burnout: differing dynamics; - Schedule flexibility opportunity; - Skills development: webside manner, virtual exam, technology proficiency;

(12) Multidisciplinary: PCP + IT + nursing + scheduling + billing + administration + patients + community + advocacy
————————————————
Telemedicine: modalities + appropriate use cases. Best practices (pre-visit, setting, webside manner, virtual exam, documentation). Technology + regulatory + reimbursement evolving. Quality + safety + equity. Special populations. Practice integration. Provider considerations. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Disaster + Emergency Preparedness Primary Care (ASPR + CDC + AAFP):

(1) Types disasters/emergencies: - Natural: hurricanes, floods, earthquakes, wildfires, tornadoes, blizzards, extreme heat/cold, drought; - Public health: pandemics (COVID-19), endemic outbreaks (measles, foodborne), bioterrorism; - Technological: power outages, cyber attacks, water contamination, transportation accidents, chemical/radiation; - Mass casualty: shootings, terrorism; - Combined: refugee crises, war;

(2) Phases of disaster cycle: - Mitigation (reduce risk); - Preparedness (planning); - Response (acute); - Recovery (long-term);

(3) Primary care role: - Continuity of care: maintain access for patients during/after; medication refills, chronic disease management; - Surge capacity: handle increased volume during outbreaks; - Triage + screening; - Vaccination delivery: outbreak + routine; - Mental health support: acute trauma + chronic; - Communications: with patients, public health, hospital; - Vulnerable populations: medically dependent, oxygen, dialysis, mental health, homeless, immigrants, elderly, disabled, low-income;

(4) Practice preparedness plan elements: - All-hazards approach: flexible framework; - Staff training + drills; - Communication plan: internal staff, patient outreach (text, social, website), referral partners, public health, suppliers; - Continuity of operations (COOP): alternate site, remote work, paper backup, key personnel; - EHR + data backup + cybersecurity; - Supply chain: medications, vaccines, PPE, basic supplies; - Power + utilities backup planning; - Medication continuity for patients (e.g., chronic medications stockpile, refill protocols, mail order, partnerships); - Mutual aid agreements; - Patient outreach for chronic conditions (HF, COPD, DM, dialysis, oxygen-dependent); - Mental health response; - Public health collaboration;

(5) Pandemic-specific (COVID lessons): - Telemedicine rapid implementation; - Outpatient testing + triage; - Infection prevention + PPE; - Vaccination delivery mass + accessible; - Long COVID management; - Health equity — disparities amplified; - Workforce wellness + burnout; - Misinformation counter;

(6) Climate change health impacts: - Heat-related illness + heat waves; - Vector-borne expansion (Lyme, dengue, etc.); - Air quality (wildfire smoke, ozone, particulate); - Allergies worsening; - Mental health (climate anxiety, displacement); - Water + food security; - Migration + conflict; - Address adaptation + advocacy;

(7) Bioterrorism awareness: - Recognize unusual presentations (anthrax, plague, smallpox, tularemia, botulism, viral hemorrhagic); - Report immediately to public health; - Personal protection;

(8) Mass casualty preparation: - Active shooter / Stop the Bleed training; - Triage + first aid; - Mental health support;

(9) Recovery + long-term: - Continued mental health (PTSD); - Chronic disease decompensation; - Health system rebuilding; - Equity considerations;

(10) National framework: - ESF #8 (Health + Medical) under Stafford Act; - National Response Framework; - HHS ASPR (Administration for Strategic Preparedness + Response); - State + local public health departments; - HPP (Hospital Preparedness Program); - PHEP (Public Health Emergency Preparedness);

(11) Resources: ASPR TRACIE, CDC Emergency Preparedness, AAFP Disaster Resources, Healthcare Coalitions;

(12) Multidisciplinary: PCP + emergency management + public health + hospital + EMS + community partners + government + faith + business + nonprofits
