(10) Advocacy + civic engagement: - Professional associations AAFP, ACP, AAP, AOA, AMA, specialty; - Federal: Congress, agencies (CMS, FDA, HHS, HRSA, CDC); - State: medical societies, legislature, governor, public health; - Local: city/county, school boards, community boards; - Coalitions: cross-specialty, patient groups, public health; - Direct patient impact: SDOH addressing, community partnerships, voter registration in healthcare settings (NoHealthyWithoutVotes);

(11) Skills for policy engagement: - Understanding legislation + regulation; - Communication with policymakers; - Op-eds + media; - Testimony; - Coalition building; - Research + evidence translation;

(12) Resources: AAFP Advocacy, ACP Health Policy + Advocacy, KFF (Kaiser Family Foundation), Commonwealth Fund, Health Affairs, NEJM Catalyst;

(13) Multidisciplinary advocacy: clinicians + administrators + patients + community + public health + policy + legal + academia + media
————————————————
Healthcare policy: major laws (Medicare/Medicaid, ACA, MACRA, HITECH, IRA). Coverage gaps. Drug pricing. Primary care priorities (payment, workforce, mental health, SDOH, equity). Public health funding. Global comparisons. Equity + climate + reproductive. Advocacy skills. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Women's Health Across Lifespan Integrative Primary Care:

(1) Family medicine well-positioned for women's lifespan care — continuity across stages;

(2) Reproductive years: - Preconception health: optimization 3+ mo before — folate 400 mcg (4 mg if NTD risk), chronic disease optimization (DM, HT, thyroid, mental health), medication review (teratogen replacement), vaccinations update (MMR if non-immune, varicella, COVID), lifestyle (smoking, alcohol, weight, nutrition, exercise), genetic carrier screening, mental health, IPV screen; - Contraception: comprehensive options + LARC counseling + risk-benefit + medical eligibility; - Reproductive autonomy + decisions; - Infertility evaluation: starts after 12 mo (6 mo if > 35), basic workup PCP + refer REI; - Menstrual + gynecologic: PMS/PMDD, dysmenorrhea, AUB, dysfunctional bleeding, endometriosis, fibroids, PCOS; - Sexual health: function, dyspareunia, libido, sexual orientation, education; - STI screening + prevention + treatment; - Cancer screening: cervical + breast;

(3) Pregnancy + postpartum: - Antenatal care: comprehensive routine + risk-based; - Hypertensive disorders pregnancy: preeclampsia, gestational HTN, chronic HTN; surveillance + management; Future CV risk marker; - Gestational DM: screening + management + postpartum follow-up + lifelong T2DM risk; - Mental health pregnancy + postpartum: high prevalence; screen + treat (SSRI, therapy); postpartum psychosis emergency; PPA; - Substance use: screening + treatment; tobacco, alcohol, opioids (MOUD); - IPV: screen; pregnancy + postpartum high-risk window; - Postpartum 4th trimester (ACOG 2018): comprehensive ongoing care;

(4) Midlife (40s-50s): - Cancer screening: breast (lower age), cervical, colon (45+), skin; - CV risk assessment: ASCVD; lipid; BP; DM; metabolic syndrome; - Bone health: foundation for osteoporosis prevention; calcium + vit D + weight-bearing; - Mental health: depression + anxiety high in midlife women; perimenopausal mood symptoms; - Sexual health: ongoing; menopause approaching; - Perimenopause: 4-8 yr transition; irregular menses, vasomotor symptoms beginning, mood, sleep;

(5) Menopause + postmenopause: - Symptoms: vasomotor, GSM, sleep, mood, cognition, joint, sexual; - MHT (see separate — NAMS 2022) — < 60 yo or < 10 yr from menopause symptomatic; transdermal preferred; - Non-hormonal options: SSRI, gabapentin, fezolinetant new, lifestyle, CBT; - Bone health: DXA at 65 (younger if risk); FRAX; treat osteoporosis; - CV: lipid + BP + DM + ASCVD risk + statin; - Cancer screening continued; - Sexual health: GSM treatment (local vaginal estrogen safe even in BC history); ospemifene, prasterone; - Cognitive aging: lifestyle + monitor; - Pelvic floor: incontinence, prolapse — PT first-line; - Mental health: ongoing;

(6) Older adults (65+): - Geriatric considerations: see separate; - Cancer screening individualized + life expectancy; - Osteoporosis management ongoing; - CV ongoing; - Cognitive screening Mini-Cog/MoCA; - Falls assessment + prevention; - Polypharmacy management Beers; - Caregiver role common; - Advance care planning;

(7) Common across lifespan: - Mental health: depression + anxiety higher in women across lifespan; trauma + IPV; - Autoimmune disease higher in women; - Migraine higher; - Body image + eating: lifespan; - Caregiving + family: integrate; - Health equity + disparities: maternal mortality (Black 3-4x), heart disease (often underrecognized in women), other; - Reproductive justice + access: lifespan;

(8) LGBTQ+ + gender-diverse: affirming care across lifespan;

(9) Cultural humility + diverse populations;

(10) Multidisciplinary integrative team: family medicine + OB/GYN + breast + REI + endocrine + cardiology + behavioral health + nutrition + PT (pelvic floor) + social work + community + family + caregivers
————————————————
Women's lifespan integrative: family medicine well-positioned. Preconception → pregnancy → postpartum → midlife → menopause → older adult. Reproductive, cancer screening, CV/bone, mental health, sexual health across stages. Equity + disparities focus. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Men's Health Across Lifespan Integrative Primary Care:

(1) Men underutilize primary care + worse outcomes — avoidance, stigma, work-prioritization, masculinity norms; engaging is opportunity;

(2) Young adult (18-39): - Lifestyle: smoking + alcohol + substance use + driving safety + sexual health + STI + mental health + injury prevention; - Establish primary care relationship; - Vaccinations (HPV catch-up to 26 + shared 27-45, Tdap, flu, COVID, meningococcal college); - Reproductive health + contraception (partner) + STI screening; - Mental health screening + suicide (highest age group); - Substance use screening; - Testicular self-exam (controversial USPSTF) — awareness of CA young; - Skin cancer awareness;

(3) Middle adult (40-64) — major chronic disease emergence: - CV risk assessment + management: BP screening, lipid (ASCVD risk), DM screening (35-70), statin per risk, smoking cessation, lifestyle; - Cancer screening: - Colorectal 45-75 (USPSTF lowered); - Lung CT 50-80 + 20 pack-year smoker; - Prostate 55-69 shared decision; high-risk (Black, family, BRCA) earlier; - Skin, oral, testicular awareness; - DM + obesity: screening + lifestyle intervention; DPP for prediabetes; medication including GLP-1 RA for obesity; - Mental health: depression + anxiety screening; suicide higher rate; substance use including alcohol; - Sexual health: ED screening (window to CVD), testosterone (true hypogonadism only), STI; - Reproductive: vasectomy counseling, fertility preservation pre-treatment; - Workplace + occupational: hazards, ergonomics, stress; - Sleep: OSA more common men; - Vaccinations: continue + age-based;

(4) Older adult (65+): - Geriatric care principles (see separate); - Cancer screening individualized + life expectancy: stop most after age 75-85 or life expectancy < 10 yr; - CV ongoing; - Osteoporosis: men 70+ (or earlier if risk — hypogonadism, glucocorticoids, antiandrogen therapy); - Falls assessment; - Cognitive screening; - BPH + LUTS management; - Polypharmacy management; - Caregiving role; - Advance care planning; - Mental health + isolation: widower depression; suicide elevated;

(5) Cross-lifespan issues: - Smoking: leading preventable cause; cessation; - Cardiovascular most common cause of death; - Mental health: underdiagnosed + undertreated; suicide rates higher men (especially older); depression presents differently (irritability, work issues, substance, somatic); - Substance use: higher rates; address; - Injury + violence: prevention; firearms; - Sexual + reproductive: lifespan; - LGBTQ+ men: affirming care; specific health considerations; - Men of color: disparities (life expectancy, prostate CA — Black men higher risk, CV); cultural humility; - Veterans: specific exposures + mental health + trauma; PTSD; access to VA; - Workplace + occupational: hazards + stress + chemical exposures; - Caregiving + family: increasing role for men; supportive;

(6) Engagement strategies: - Meet patients where they are; - Honest + practical; - Sports + work metaphors when fit; - Reduce stigma; - Address barriers (time, cost, access); - Use other touch points (employer, sports physical, partner appointment); - Outreach + reminders;

(7) Specific cancer awareness: - Testicular CA — young men, self-exam awareness; - Prostate CA — shared decision PSA + family history; - Penile CA — uncommon but awareness; - Male breast CA — uncommon, family history BRCA; - Skin CA; - Colorectal; - Lung;

(8) Sexual + reproductive health: - ED — window to CVD; - Testosterone — only if confirmed hypogonadism; - Infertility — workup + REI; - STI screening + prevention; - PrEP for high-risk; - LGBTQ+ + MSM-specific: see separate;

(9) Pediatric to adult transition for young men chronic conditions;

(10) Multidisciplinary integrative: family medicine + urology + cardiology + behavioral health + endocrinology + oncology + community + family + workplace + male-oriented programs
————————————————
Men's health lifespan: underutilize care — engagement strategies. Young adult — lifestyle + mental health + sexual. Middle adult — chronic disease + cancer screening + ED + mental health. Older adult — geriatric principles + BPH + falls. Cross-lifespan (CV, mental health, substance, sexual). Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Refugee + Immigrant Primary Care Integrative (CDC + AAFP + Society for Refugee Healthcare Providers):

(1) Categories: refugees (UNHCR-designated), asylees, asylum-seekers, immigrants (documented + undocumented), TPS (temporary protected status), parolees, others;

(2) Pre-arrival: - Refugees: medical exam abroad — TB, syphilis, gonorrhea, leprosy, HIV (not exclusionary now); - Vaccinations per CDC requirements; - Domestic medical screening comprehensive within 30-90 days arrival (state programs);

(3) Comprehensive initial assessment: - History: country of origin, ethnicity, language, refugee experience (camp duration, journey), pre-migration trauma, family separation, current resettlement; - Physical exam comprehensive; - Screening: - Infectious: - TB (IGRA or TST) — high prevalence many countries; LTBI treatment; - HBV, HCV, HIV screening — variable by country; - Syphilis + STIs; - Parasites (stool O&P, schistosomiasis serology endemic areas, strongyloidiasis especially before steroid/biologic — empirical ivermectin for refugees from endemic some recommend); - Malaria endemic; - Country-specific: e.g., Chagas Latin America; - Hematologic: CBC, hemoglobinopathy screening (thalassemia + sickle cell endemic areas), G6PD before primaquine/dapsone; - Vitamin deficiency: D, B12, iron — high prevalence; - Lead (children especially); - Mental health: PTSD, depression, anxiety — high prevalence; refugee-specific scales (RHS-15, HSCL-25); torture history; - Dental + oral — often unmet; - Vision + hearing — refractive errors common, may be untreated; - Reproductive health: contraception, prenatal care, female genital cutting (sensitive assessment + management); - Vaccinations: catch-up per CDC schedule; document acceptance varies;

(4) Common conditions: - Vitamin D deficiency very common; - Latent TB common; - Mental health PTSD, depression; - Chronic disease (HT, DM, CV) — often unmanaged + worsening; - Cancer screening often never done; - Untreated chronic conditions: thyroid, anemia, etc.; - Reproductive health unmet needs;

(5) Cultural humility + practices: - Diverse beliefs about health + illness + body; - Religious + spiritual considerations (Ramadan, prayer times, dietary halal/kosher, modesty, gender concordance providers preferred some); - Traditional healing integration; - Family + community dynamics; - Migration trauma + ongoing acculturation stress; - Discrimination + xenophobia;

(6) Trauma-informed care: - High prevalence trauma (torture, violence, sexual, witnessing); - Triggers in healthcare; - Safety + trust + choice + collaboration + empowerment; - PTSD screening + treatment (EMDR, CBT, medications); - Center for Victims of Torture + similar resources;

(7) Language access: - Professional interpreters mandatory — Title VI requirement federally-funded; - Video, phone, in-person; - NOT family or children; - Cultural brokers; - Written materials in language;

(8) Legal + social complexity: - Immigration status + healthcare access; - Public charge concerns (chilling effect on services); - Employment + housing + food + transportation; - Family reunification; - Asylum process + medical evaluation (Physicians for Human Rights training for asylum medical/psychological evaluations); - Healthcare access for undocumented limited (emergency Medicaid + community resources);

(9) Refugee-specific resources + benefits: - RMA (Refugee Medical Assistance) — 8 mo healthcare benefits federally funded; - State-specific extended benefits; - Refugee Resettlement Agencies; - Community + faith-based partners;

(10) Pediatric considerations: - Vaccinations catch-up; - Growth + nutrition; - Developmental screening; - Education + school enrollment; - Trauma in children; - Family reunification;

(11) Special populations: - Unaccompanied minors: complex; - LGBTQ+ refugees: persecution-specific; - Survivors of torture + trafficking; - Women + girls: gender-based violence, FGC; - Older refugees: isolation, dependency;

(12) Long-term integration: chronic disease management as integration progresses; cultural broker role; advocacy;

(13) Multidisciplinary: PCP + community health worker / cultural broker + interpreter + behavioral health + social work + legal + community partners + religious + family + specialty referrals + public health + resettlement agencies
————————————————
Refugee/immigrant care: comprehensive initial screening (TB, parasites, vitamin D, mental health, chronic disease). Trauma-informed essential. Cultural humility. Professional interpreters. Legal + social complexity. Refugee-specific benefits + resources. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Group Visits / Shared Medical Appointments (SMA) Integrative Care:

(1) Definition: physician-led group visit where multiple patients with similar conditions receive medical care + education + peer support together; can include other team members;

(2) Evidence: improved outcomes T2DM, HTN, HF, depression, chronic pain, prenatal care, weight management; cost-effective;

(3) Models: - Drop-in Group Medical Appointment (DIGMA): ongoing, mixed conditions, regular schedule; - Cooperative Health Care Clinic (CHCC): closed cohort same patients over time; - Physical SMA (PSMA): includes individual physical exam component; - Specialty + condition-specific: prenatal (Centering Pregnancy), DM, HTN, HF, depression, pain, weight, smoking cessation, behavioral health;

(4) Components: - Group education by team; - Peer interaction + support; - Individual physician encounter within or separate; - Team-based care — RN, dietitian, behavioral health, pharmacy as needed; - Goal-setting + accountability; - Self-management focus; - Cultural + language matching when possible;

(5) Advantages: - Patient: peer support + learning, more time with provider (90 min vs 15), normalization, accountability, social connection; - Provider: education efficiency, address common issues once, team-based, reduced burnout; - System: efficiency, access, reduced ED visits + hospitalizations, cost-effective; - Outcomes: improved A1c, BP, adherence, self-efficacy, satisfaction;

(6) Setup considerations: - Space: large enough for group + privacy; - Time: 90-120 min typical; - Frequency: weekly to monthly; - Group size: 6-15 typical; - Recruitment: screen + enroll, address transportation, scheduling; - Confidentiality + ground rules: HIPAA, group agreements; - Documentation: each individual encounter; - Billing: typically code each individual; some states offer specific codes; - Technology: virtual SMA growing — telegroups;

(7) Patient selection: - Common diagnosis or interest; - Mix of stages (engagement + role model); - Voluntary; - Address barriers;

(8) Specific examples + evidence: - Centering Pregnancy — well-established, improved birth outcomes (lower preterm + LBW), satisfaction; - DM SMAs — improved A1c + other markers; - HTN SMAs; - Chronic pain group programs — Living Well; - Behavioral health groups — depression, anxiety, mindfulness, CBT; - Weight management — DPP group format; - Cardiac rehab + pulmonary rehab — group-based; - Substance use treatment: AA, MAT groups; - Smoking cessation groups; - CHWs + peer support programs;

(9) Cultural + linguistic adaptation: - Language-concordant groups; - Cultural framing of content; - Community + faith partnerships;

(10) Integration with population health management: identify panel members + outreach + enroll;

(11) Provider training: facilitation, group dynamics, time management;

(12) Patient engagement + sustainability: address dropout, peer leaders, ongoing recruitment;

(13) Equity + access: address transportation, childcare, language, cost; reach underserved;

(14) Multidisciplinary: PCP + APP + nursing + dietitian + behavioral health + pharmacy + CHW + administration + patients (peer leaders, advisors)
————————————————
Group visits / SMA: physician-led group care with peer support. Multiple models. Evidence-based for DM, HTN, prenatal, etc. Components: education + peer + individual encounter + team. Advantages — patient, provider, system. Setup + selection + billing. Equity. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Behavioral Health Integration (BHI) — Collaborative Care Model (Unützer + APA + AIMS Center):

(1) Need: mental health in primary care; ~ 50% mental health care delivered in primary care; specialty access limited; outcomes traditionally suboptimal;

(2) Continuum of integration (SAMHSA-HRSA 4-quadrant): - Level 1: Minimal collaboration — separate; - Level 2: Basic collaboration at distance — referral with limited communication; - Level 3: Basic collaboration on-site — co-located; - Level 4: Close collaboration on-site with shared system; - Level 5: Close collaboration approaching integration; - Level 6: Full collaboration in transformed/merged integrated practice; - Higher level = better outcomes for moderate-severe conditions;

(3) Collaborative Care Model (CoCM) — most evidence: - 5 core principles: - Patient-centered team care; - Population-based care (registry); - Measurement-based care + treat-to-target (PHQ-9, GAD-7 routine); - Evidence-based care; - Accountable care; - Team members: - PCP — primary clinical management; - Behavioral Health Care Manager — RN, social worker, psychologist — care management, brief interventions, follow-up, registry; - Psychiatric Consultant — weekly case review with care manager, recommendations to PCP, direct consultation for complex;

(4) Evidence Collaborative Care: > 80 RCTs across conditions + settings — better outcomes vs usual care for depression, anxiety, substance use, PTSD, dementia + caregiver; pediatric; perinatal; chronic disease comorbid; veterans; rural;

(5) CMS Collaborative Care codes (BHI 99492-99494) support reimbursement; many private insurance;

(6) Implementation steps: - Assess practice readiness; - Identify champions + leadership; - Workflow design + EHR integration; - Hire/train care manager + psychiatric consultant; - Universal screening (PHQ-9, GAD-7, CRAFFT, others); - Registry + measurement; - Quality improvement ongoing; - Patient engagement; - Reimbursement strategy;

(7) Alternative integrated models: - Primary Care Behavioral Health (PCBH) — behavioral health provider embedded; brief interventions; warm handoffs; broader population; less specialized depression focus; - Co-location without integration — basic; - Bidirectional integration — primary care in mental health settings;

(8) Specific applications: - Depression — most evidence; - Anxiety; - PTSD + trauma; - Substance use disorders: MAT for OUD (buprenorphine), AUD pharmacotherapy + counseling; - Chronic pain + mental health comorbidity; - Severe mental illness in primary care: schizophrenia, bipolar; primary care of medical comorbidities + co-management with psychiatry; - Pediatric: family-based, school integration; - Perinatal: postpartum depression; - Geriatric: depression, dementia, caregiver support; - Substance use disorders: SBIRT + MAT; - Chronic disease: DM + depression, etc. — depression treatment improves both;

(9) Specific evidence-based interventions delivered by BHI team: - Brief CBT; - Behavioral activation; - Problem-solving therapy; - Motivational interviewing; - Mindfulness; - Sleep hygiene + CBT-I; - Substance use brief intervention; - Self-management coaching;

(10) Pharmacotherapy support: PCP-prescribed with consultation; medication monitoring; adherence support;

(11) Quality measures: PHQ-9 response + remission, GAD-7, screening rates, treatment initiation + intensification, suicide risk assessment;

(12) Equity + access: BHI improves access to mental health especially for underserved + minorities + rural; addresses stigma;

(13) Technology: tele-mental health, apps (Calm, Headspace, computerized CBT — Beating the Blues), digital therapeutics;

(14) Workforce considerations: care manager workforce + training + reimbursement adequate; psychiatry workforce shortage so consultation model efficient;

(15) Resources: AIMS Center (University of Washington), APA Integrated Care, SAMHSA-HRSA Center for Integrated Health Solutions;

(16) Multidisciplinary: PCP + behavioral health care manager + psychiatric consultant + APP + nursing + social work + community resources + family + patient + payers + leadership
————————————————
BHI Collaborative Care Model: PCP + care manager + psychiatric consultant. 5 core principles. Strong evidence depression + anxiety + others. Implementation. Alternative models (PCBH). Specific applications + pharm + non-pharm interventions. CMS reimbursement codes. Equity. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): End-of-Life Care Integrative Family-Centered (NHPCO + CAPC + Ariadne):

(1) Goals-of-care conversation central + ongoing: - Reframe from disease focus to person + values; - Hopes + worries + tradeoffs framework; - 'I wish + I worry + I wonder' phrases; - Family + caregiver involvement; - Cultural + spiritual considerations; - Document + revisit as condition changes; - Serious Illness Conversation Guide (Ariadne);

(2) Hospice eligibility + benefit: - Prognosis ≤ 6 mo if disease takes natural course; - Patient + family agreement on comfort focus; - Medicare hospice benefit since 1982 — most insurance covers similarly; - Disease-specific Local Coverage Determinations (LCDs): cancer, dementia, CHF, COPD, liver, kidney, stroke, debility; - Hospice team: physician, nurse, social worker, chaplain, aide, volunteer, bereavement counselor, therapists; - Settings: home (most common), nursing facility, inpatient hospice, hospital (rare); - Levels: routine home, continuous home, inpatient respite, general inpatient (for symptom crisis);

(3) Symptom management — see palliative care: pain, dyspnea, nausea, constipation, fatigue, anorexia, anxiety, delirium, spiritual distress;

(4) Active dying phase: - Signs: decreased consciousness, decreased intake, mottling, terminal secretions, Cheyne-Stokes breathing, restlessness, decreased urine, cool extremities; - Anticipatory guidance for family — expected, peaceful; - Comfort measures: medications for pain, dyspnea, secretions (scopolamine, glycopyrrolate); positioning; mouth care; - Hydration / nutrition: artificial generally not beneficial actively dying — discuss expectations; - Discontinue non-essential medications + monitoring; - Withdraw burdensome interventions as appropriate (cardiac monitor, IVs, BP checks, finger sticks);

(5) Family + caregiver support integral: - Pre-death: education, anticipatory grief, emotional + practical support; - Bedside vigil: meaningful, supportive; - Death: notify family; provide privacy; honor cultural + religious practices; - Post-death: notify physician (or hospice MD pronounces); body care; mortuary; - Bereavement support: 13 months hospice (Medicare); ongoing groups + counseling; complicated grief identification + referral;

(6) Spiritual + existential care: - Chaplaincy integral hospice; - Religious + cultural practices at end of life — diverse; ask + honor; - Existential dignity work: life review, dignity therapy, meaning-making, music/art, legacy; - Mindfulness + meditation; - Connection + relationships;

(7) Specific scenarios: - Sudden / unexpected death: traumatic; immediate support family; followup; - Death of child / infant: devastating; specialized perinatal palliative + pediatric palliative; - Suicide (recent): family complex grief; support; reduce stigma + blame; - Mass casualty / disaster deaths;

(8) Voluntarily stopping eating and drinking (VSED): option in some patients; respect autonomy; supportive care; - Medical aid in dying (MAID) — legal in 10 US states + DC + several countries; differs from euthanasia (illegal US); strict eligibility + safeguards; family medicine often involved when legal + comfortable; - Palliative sedation for refractory suffering — ethical + accepted (not euthanasia); intentions transparent;

(9) Pediatric end-of-life: - Specific challenges; - Family + sibling support; - Decision-making by parents — challenging; - School + community support; - Specialty pediatric palliative + hospice;

(10) Equity in end-of-life care: - Disparities by race, ethnicity, SES, geography; - Black + Hispanic + Asian patients + families different preferences/utilization; - Cultural humility critical; - Access barriers; - Healthcare proxy + advance directives less common in some communities;

(11) Provider self-care + grief: cumulative loss; debriefing; institutional support; primary care relationships make end-of-life care deeply meaningful + emotionally demanding;

(12) Quality measures end-of-life: hospice length of stay (very short = late referral), preferred place of death achieved, family satisfaction;

(13) Family medicine well-positioned: relationship continuity, family unit care, holistic, comfort with whole-person care;

(14) Multidisciplinary integrative: PCP + hospice MD + RN + SW + chaplain + aide + volunteer + family + extended family + community + religious community + bereavement + pediatric (if pediatric)
————————————————
End-of-life integrative: goals-of-care central. Hospice for ≤ 6 mo prognosis. Active dying signs + management. Family + caregiver support throughout. Spiritual + existential. VSED / MAID where legal. Pediatric. Equity. Provider self-care. Family medicine well-positioned. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Outpatient Hyperkalemia Management:

(1) Severity: mild 5.5-5.9, moderate 6.0-6.4, severe ≥ 6.5 or any ECG changes or symptoms — affects urgency;

(2) Confirm: rule out pseudohyperkalemia (hemolysis, prolonged tourniquet, fist clenching, K-EDTA contamination, thrombocytosis, leukocytosis) — repeat properly + plasma vs serum if concern;

(3) ECG indications: K ≥ 6, symptoms, rapid change; look for peaked T waves → loss of P → wide QRS → sine wave (severe); ECG changes need IMMEDIATE treatment regardless of level;

(4) Causes: - Renal — CKD, AKI; - Medications (most common modifiable in outpatient): ACEi/ARB, K-sparing diuretics (spironolactone, eplerenone, amiloride), MRA (finerenone), TMP-SMX, NSAIDs, heparin, beta-blockers, calcineurin inhibitors, succinylcholine; - Adrenal insufficiency; - Acidosis; - Hyperglycemia (insulin deficiency); - Cell breakdown (rhabdo, tumor lysis, hemolysis); - Excess intake usually with kidney impairment;

(5) Asymptomatic mild-moderate without ECG changes (this patient) outpatient: - Dietary K restriction counseling (limit bananas, potatoes, tomatoes, oranges, melon, spinach, beans, salt substitutes — KCl content); - Loop diuretic (furosemide) — kaliuretic; - K binders — modern outpatient option: - Patiromer (Veltassa) — non-absorbable polymer; slow onset; good for chronic; allows continuation RAAS therapy; - Sodium zirconium cyclosilicate (Lokelma) — newer, faster onset; - SPS (Kayexalate) — older, GI side effects (concern bowel ischemia); replaced by newer agents often; - Address underlying: adjust offending medications (don't blindly stop ACEi in HF/CKD — assess benefit-risk; new binders allow continuation); - Treat acidosis if present (bicarbonate selected);

(6) Severe (≥ 6.5 or ECG changes) — ED/hospital: - Calcium gluconate IV — membrane stabilization (no K-lowering); - Insulin + glucose — shifts K intracellular; - Beta-2 agonist (albuterol nebulizer 10-20 mg) — shifts; - Bicarbonate if acidosis; - Diuretic + K binder for removal; - Dialysis for severe / refractory / ESRD;

(7) Re-evaluation: recheck K in 1-2 wk; monitor with chronic treatment;

(8) RAAS continuation in CKD + HF: balance with K management — emerging data K binders allow safe continuation with mortality benefit (don't reflexively stop without alternative strategy);

(9) Patient education: dietary, medication adherence, recognize symptoms (palpitations, weakness, paralysis); avoid salt substitutes (KCl);

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + nephrology + cardiology + dietitian + pharmacy
————————————————
Hyperkalemia: severity + ECG + cause assessment. Pseudo? Mild-mod outpatient — dietary, loop diuretic, new K binders (patiromer, ZS-9) allow RAAS continuation. Severe → ED (Ca, insulin/glucose, beta-agonist, dialysis). Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (AAOS + AAN):

(1) Diagnosis clinical primarily: - Symptoms: median nerve distribution numbness/paresthesia (thumb, index, middle, lateral ring), often worse at night/with activities, hand shaking relief, weakness/clumsiness; - Provocative tests: Phalen (90 sec wrist flexion), Tinel (percuss median nerve), Durkan compression (most specific); thenar atrophy (severe/chronic);

(2) Risk factors: F > M, age, obesity, pregnancy, DM, hypothyroidism, RA, dialysis, amyloidosis, repetitive wrist activities, vibration;

(3) Differential: cervical radiculopathy (C6-7), thoracic outlet, ulnar neuropathy, peripheral neuropathy, brachial plexopathy;

(4) Workup: - Clinical diagnosis sufficient many cases; - EMG/NCS — gold standard if uncertain, severe, surgical consideration, refractory, atypical, occupational/legal documentation; - US of median nerve — increasingly used (cross-sectional area ≥ 9-10 mm²); - MRI atypical; - Labs selectively: TSH (hypothyroid), HbA1c (DM), CBC + RF + ANA (autoimmune), vit B12; pregnancy assessment;

(5) Conservative management first (mild-moderate): - Wrist splinting (neutral position) — especially nighttime; modest evidence; - Activity modification + ergonomics: keyboard, mouse, repetitive grip; workplace; - NSAIDs / acetaminophen for symptoms; - Local corticosteroid injection (1-2/yr) — short-term effective; - Oral corticosteroid short course — modest evidence; - PT — nerve gliding exercises; - Address underlying: treat hypothyroid, glucose control;

(6) Surgery (open or endoscopic carpal tunnel release) for: - Severe / persistent / refractory; - Significant motor weakness or atrophy; - Severe sensory loss; - Failure conservative; - High-risk for permanent dysfunction; - Effective + outpatient procedure;

(7) Postoperative: PT, gradual return to activity, expect improvement weeks-months;

(8) Pregnancy-related: usually resolves postpartum — conservative (splint);

(9) Occupational considerations: ergonomic assessment, workplace modification, workers' compensation if applicable;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + hand surgeon (ortho or plastic) + PT/OT + occupational medicine if work-related
————————————————
Carpal tunnel: clinical diagnosis (provocative tests). EMG/NCS if uncertain/surgical. Conservative first (splint, ergonomics, steroid injection, NSAIDs). Surgery for severe/refractory/motor weakness. Address underlying conditions. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Psoriasis + Psoriatic Arthritis Management (AAD 2019 + 2023 update + ACR):

(1) Diagnosis clinical: well-demarcated erythematous plaques with silvery scale; typical distribution (extensor surfaces, scalp, nails, intergluteal); Auspitz sign (bleeding from removal scale);

(2) Severity classification: - Mild (BSA < 3%); - Moderate (BSA 3-10%); - Severe (BSA > 10% or significant impact); - PASI (Psoriasis Area + Severity Index); - DLQI (impact); - Comorbidity assessment: psoriatic arthritis (~ 30%), CV (increased risk independent), metabolic syndrome, NAFLD, IBD, depression, anxiety, substance use;

(3) Psoriatic arthritis screening + diagnosis (CASPAR criteria): joint pain + psoriasis + nail dystrophy + dactylitis (sausage digit) + enthesitis + family history; PsA screening tools (PEST, PASE) at each visit; refer rheumatology + ortho;

(4) Treatment by severity: - Mild — topical: - Topical corticosteroids — first-line (potency by site — high body, low face/groin/intertriginous); - Vitamin D analogs (calcipotriene); - Combination calcipotriene + betamethasone (Taclonex); - Topical calcineurin inhibitor (tacrolimus, pimecrolimus) — face, intertriginous; - Topical retinoid (tazarotene) — combo with steroid; - Coal tar, salicylic acid alternatives; - Topical PDE-4 inhibitor (roflumilast) — newer 2022; - Topical aryl hydrocarbon receptor agonist (tapinarof — VTAMA) — newer 2022; - Moderate — phototherapy + systemic option: - NBUVB phototherapy — first-line non-systemic; - Excimer laser localized; - PUVA alternative; - Severe / refractory / PsA / nail / palmoplantar / scalp severe — systemic: - Methotrexate — historical workhorse + PsA; LFT + CBC monitoring; folate; teratogen; - Cyclosporine short-term; - Apremilast (Otezla — PDE-4) oral; - Acitretin (retinoid) — teratogen 3 yr; - Biologics (revolutionary): - TNF inhibitors (adalimumab, etanercept, infliximab, certolizumab, golimumab) — also PsA + IBD; - IL-17 inhibitors (secukinumab, ixekizumab, brodalumab) — highly effective psoriasis; PsA; - IL-23 inhibitors (guselkumab, risankizumab, tildrakizumab) — highly effective, less frequent dosing; - IL-12/23 inhibitor (ustekinumab); - JAK inhibitors (deucravacitinib — TYK2 — oral; tofacitinib, upadacitinib for PsA); - Comparing biologics: head-to-head trials — IL-17 + IL-23 often higher efficacy than TNF for skin; TNF + JAK better for PsA + IBD; - Screening before biologics: TB, hepatitis B/C, HIV, vaccinations;

(5) Comorbidity management critical: - CV risk assessment + management (independent ↑ ~ 20-50%) — statin + BP + DM + smoking + weight + exercise; - PsA — refer rheumatology, DMARD + biologic; - Metabolic + NAFLD; - Mental health: depression + anxiety + substance use; - IBD: screen + co-manage; - Vaccinations: avoid live on biologics;

(6) Lifestyle: weight (psoriasis improves), Mediterranean diet, alcohol moderation, smoking cessation, stress management;

(7) Pregnancy: certolizumab (preferred — minimal placental), other biologics individual; methotrexate teratogen 3 mo washout;

(8) Multidisciplinary: PCP + dermatology + rheumatology + cardiology + mental health + nutrition + GI + pharmacy
————————————————
Psoriasis: severity stratified. Topical (steroid + vit D + calcineurin + newer roflumilast/tapinarof). Phototherapy. Systemic (MTX, biologics revolutionary — TNF + IL-17 + IL-23 + JAK). PsA screening + treatment. CV + metabolic + mental health comorbidity. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Chronic Otitis Media Management (AAO-HNS):

(1) Chronic suppurative otitis media (CSOM): chronic TM perforation + intermittent/persistent otorrhea ≥ 2 wk;

(2) Cholesteatoma — separate entity, can be congenital or acquired (more concerning): keratinized squamous epithelium in middle ear; can erode bone + cause complications (hearing loss, CN VII palsy, vertigo, meningitis, brain abscess, lateral sinus thrombosis); white/pearly mass in retraction pocket; CT temporal bone for evaluation + extent;

(3) Workup: otoscopy + microsuction; pneumatic otoscopy / tympanometry (limited if perf); audiogram; cultures of drainage; CT temporal bone for cholesteatoma / complications;

(4) Medical management: - Topical antibiotic drops with steroid: ofloxacin (Floxin), ciprofloxacin + dexamethasone (Ciprodex) — safe with perforation; - Avoid aminoglycoside drops with perforation (potentially ototoxic); - Aural toilet (debridement, suction); - Keep ear dry — water precautions; - Treat 7-14 d typically; chronic may need longer;

(5) Surgical management: - Cholesteatoma — surgical removal (tympanomastoidectomy) — essential to prevent complications; - Persistent perforation with hearing loss or recurrent infection → tympanoplasty; - Mastoiditis acute or chronic — IV abx + surgery if severe; - ENT specialty management;

(6) Hearing loss management: hearing aids, BAHA (bone anchored), CI selected;

(7) Complications watch: - Mastoiditis; - Facial palsy; - Labyrinthitis (vertigo + sensorineural HL); - Petrositis (Gradenigo's triad — otorrhea + retro-orbital pain + abducens palsy); - Meningitis; - Brain abscess; - Lateral sinus thrombosis; - Otitic hydrocephalus; - These are emergencies;

(8) Pediatric considerations: chronic OM with effusion (OME) — tympanostomy tubes if persistent; speech delay;

(9) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ENT + audiology + speech pathology + neurosurgery if complications
————————————————
Chronic OM / cholesteatoma: chronic perforation + otorrhea or pearly mass. Workup: otoscopy + audiogram + CT. Topical FQ + steroid drops safe with perforation. Cholesteatoma needs surgery. Complications serious. ENT referral. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Croup (Laryngotracheobronchitis) Pediatric (AAP):

(1) Diagnosis clinical: viral (parainfluenza most common, RSV, influenza, adenovirus, SARS-CoV-2 omicron specifically); 6 mo - 6 yr; barking cough, hoarse, inspiratory stridor; URI prodrome;

(2) Severity (Westley score): - Mild: no stridor at rest, no/mild WOB, normal mental status; - Moderate: stridor at rest, mild-moderate WOB; - Severe: marked stridor, retractions, agitation/lethargy, hypoxia → emergency; - Imminent respiratory failure: cyanosis, fatigue, decreased breath sounds;

(3) Differential important to consider: - Epiglottitis (Hib — now rare with vaccine; bacterial; abrupt severe, drooling, tripod, toxic appearance — emergency airway + antibiotic); - Bacterial tracheitis — toxic + thick secretions; - Foreign body — sudden onset choking history; - Anaphylaxis — exposure + other symptoms; - Retropharyngeal abscess; - Subglottic stenosis congenital/acquired; - Spasmodic croup: recurrent, less viral, no fever;

(4) Workup: clinical, no routine imaging; lateral neck X-ray (steeple sign — subglottic narrowing) only if uncertain; avoid distress; CBC/cultures not needed routine;

(5) Treatment: - Mild (this patient): - Single dose dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg PO/IM/IV (max 16 mg) — strong evidence; reduces symptoms + return visits; equivalent oral/IM/IV; - Outpatient management with discharge; - Reassurance + return precautions; - Cool mist (older home remedy — limited evidence but used); - Honey for cough age > 1; - Moderate: - Dexamethasone + nebulized racemic epinephrine (2.25% 0.5 mL or L-epinephrine 5 mL 1:1000) — bridges 2-4 h until steroid effect; - Observe ≥ 2-4 h post-nebulizer (rebound possible); - Discharge if improved + reliable family; - Severe: - Above + admission; - Continuous nebulized epinephrine; - Higher dexamethasone or methylprednisolone; - Oxygen; - Heliox sometimes; - Intubation if respiratory failure; - ICU; - Avoid agitation in severe (worsens) — examine in caregiver's lap;

(6) Antibiotics not indicated for typical viral croup; bacterial tracheitis exception;

(7) Discharge criteria: - No stridor at rest; - Normal O2 sat; - Tolerating PO; - Reliable family; - Education + return precautions;

(8) Return precautions: stridor at rest, severe WOB, cyanosis, lethargy, inability to drink, persistent fever;

(9) Recurrent croup: consider anatomic / GERD / asthma evaluation; ENT consideration;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ED + pediatrics + ENT if recurrent / atypical + anesthesia + ICU if severe
————————————————
Croup: viral parainfluenza most common. Severity (Westley). Clinical diagnosis. Single-dose dexamethasone for all (mild oral, moderate-severe + neb epinephrine). Observe post-epi. Differentials important (epiglottitis, FB, bacterial tracheitis). Severe → admit. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Health Disparities + Structural Racism (NAM + KFF + APHA):

(1) Health disparities: differences in health outcomes between populations, often systematic, avoidable, unjust; affecting race/ethnicity, SES, gender, sexual orientation, age, ability, geography, language;

(2) Structural racism: ways societies foster racial discrimination through mutually reinforcing inequitable systems (housing, education, employment, healthcare, criminal justice, credit, etc.) — affects health beyond individual interactions; declared public health crisis by AMA + APA + CDC + multiple cities;

(3) Major disparities examples: - Maternal mortality — Black women 3-4x higher; - Infant mortality — Black infants 2x; - Life expectancy — racial + geographic gaps (Black men ~ 4-5 yr lower; gap by ZIP code can be 20+ yr); - COVID-19 — disproportionate impact communities of color; - Heart disease + DM + asthma + hypertension — disparities in incidence + outcomes; - Cancer screening + treatment + survival — disparities; - Mental health + suicide — disparities, especially youth (Black youth suicide rising); - Pain management — Black + Hispanic less likely receive adequate analgesia; - LGBTQ+ — mental health, suicide, substance, healthcare avoidance; - Disabilities — access; - Rural — workforce, access, outcomes;

(4) Drivers + frameworks: - Social determinants of health (SDOH) — 80% of health outcomes; - Structural racism + discrimination — see Bailey + Krieger, Williams; - Toxic stress + allostatic load biological consequences of chronic adversity; - ACE (Adverse Childhood Experiences) — lifetime health impact; - Historical trauma — Indigenous, Black, other communities; - Implicit bias healthcare providers — affects communication, diagnosis, treatment; - Healthcare access + quality — insurance, geography, language, cultural; - Environmental injustice — pollution, lead, food deserts, green space; - Economic — wealth gap; - Education; - Criminal justice involvement; - Housing instability;

(5) Evidence base growing: - Race as social construct, not biological — eGFR race-correction recently removed; lung function reference equations being reconsidered; vBAC calculator removed race; - Genetic ancestry vs racial identification — distinct; - Weathering hypothesis (Geronimus) — accumulated stress accelerated aging in marginalized; - Place-based health — neighborhood matters;

(6) Approaches to address — multi-level: - Individual level: - Implicit bias training — recognition; humility ongoing; - Cultural humility — see separate; - Trauma-informed care; - Affirming care (LGBTQ+, race, religion); - Communication + language access; - Patient-centered + respectful care; - Practice level: - Diverse + competent workforce; - Equity-focused QI — stratified outcomes, equity dashboard; - Address SDOH — screening + intervention + community partnerships; - CHW + cultural broker programs; - Reduce barriers (cost, transportation, language, hours, scheduling, virtual options); - Community engagement — co-design, advisory; - System level: - Insurance + access — Medicaid expansion, ACA; - Workforce + GME funding rural + underserved; - Payment models valuing equity; - HIT + EHR for equity; - Quality measures stratified; - Policy + advocacy: - Healthcare policy for coverage + access; - Housing + employment + education + criminal justice + environmental policy; - Voting rights; - Climate justice; - Reparations + restorative justice;

(7) Family medicine well-positioned: relationships, community, longitudinal, holistic;

(8) Self-reflection + lifelong learning: ongoing process;

(9) Allyship + advocacy for marginalized communities;

(10) Resources: NAM Communities in Action, Health Affairs racism series, NEJM Race + Medicine; AAFP Center for Diversity + Health Equity; KFF Disparities; Robert Wood Johnson;

(11) Multidisciplinary: clinicians + administrators + patients + community + public health + policy + academia + advocacy + government + multiple sectors
————————————————
Health disparities + structural racism: avoidable + unjust differences; major examples (maternal mortality, life expectancy, etc.). Race as social construct (eGFR de-racing). Drivers (SDOH, structural, ACEs, bias). Multi-level approaches (individual, practice, system, policy). Family medicine positioned. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Complementary + Integrative Medicine (NCCIH + ACLM):

(1) Definitions: - Complementary: along with conventional; - Alternative: instead of (concerning); - Integrative: combination evidence-based + complementary; - NCCIH (National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health) — federal research arm;

(2) Categories: - Mind-body: meditation, mindfulness, yoga, tai chi, qi gong, hypnosis, biofeedback, guided imagery; - Nutritional: herbal supplements, vitamins, minerals, special diets; - Manipulative + body-based: massage, chiropractic, osteopathic manipulation; - Energy therapies: Reiki, therapeutic touch, healing touch; - Whole medical systems: traditional Chinese medicine (acupuncture, herbs), Ayurveda, naturopathy, homeopathy;

(3) Evidence-based integrative — examples with reasonable evidence: - Mindfulness + meditation: stress, depression, anxiety, chronic pain, hypertension, hot flashes, IBS, sleep; - Yoga: chronic LBP (ACP guideline), depression, anxiety, chronic stress; - Tai chi: falls prevention elderly, OA, fibromyalgia, mood; - Acupuncture: chronic pain (LBP, neck, OA, headache — meta-analyses + ACP + NICE), nausea (pregnancy, chemo), tension headache, fibromyalgia, smoking cessation; - Massage therapy: pain, anxiety, stress; - Spinal manipulation (chiropractic/osteopathic): acute LBP (alongside other), some chronic LBP; safety considerations (rare vertebral artery dissection cervical); - Probiotics: AAD-associated diarrhea, IBS selected, Clostridioides difficile; specific strains important; - Omega-3 fish oil: triglycerides, modest CV (IPE — Vascepa); supplements vs food; - Vitamin D + Ca + others: as deficient + bone health; - Melatonin: jet lag, circadian sleep disorders, mild insomnia, delayed sleep phase; - Glucosamine + chondroitin: knee OA — controversial, ACR/AF recommends against, AAOS limited support; - St John's Wort: mild-moderate depression (drug interactions — induces CYP3A4); - SAMe: depression alternative; - CoQ10: statin myopathy modest, migraine prevention; - Magnesium: migraine prevention, leg cramps;

