(7) Patient digital health tools: - Apps for self-management (Diabetes — many; mental health — Headspace, Calm; medication reminders; menstrual; weight); - Wearables (Apple Watch, Fitbit, Garmin) — increasingly clinical-grade (ECG, AFib detection, fall, sleep, SpO2); - Connected devices (BP, glucose, scales); - Patient-reported outcomes (PROMs) integration; - Digital therapeutics (FDA-approved — Pear AKILI ADHD, Somryst insomnia, others);

(8) Telemedicine — see separate;

(9) Cybersecurity + privacy: - HIPAA compliance; - Ransomware attacks epidemic on healthcare; - Patient data breaches; - Cyber insurance; - Patient privacy in apps + wearables (FTC, FDA);

(10) Health equity in digital health: - Digital divide — access, broadband, literacy, language; - Algorithmic bias — affects marginalized; - Equity-centered design; - Multiple modalities (digital + non-digital);

(11) Provider wellness + informatics: - EHR burden top driver of burnout; - Ambient AI scribes game-changer for documentation; - EHR optimization; - Usability improving;

(12) Future direction: - Generative AI everywhere; - Continuous health monitoring (wearables + sensors); - Precision medicine (genomics + AI); - Patient empowerment + self-management; - Workforce transformation; - Equity considerations central;

(13) Multidisciplinary informatics: clinicians + informaticians + data scientists + IT + administration + patients + community + regulators + vendors + academia
————————————————
Health informatics + AI: EHR + interoperability (FHIR, TEFCA). AI applications — ambient scribes (game changer), CDS, imaging, NLP, predictive, generative LLMs. Considerations — bias, explainability, validation, equity, liability. Patient digital tools. Cybersecurity. Burnout reduction. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Quaternary Prevention + Choosing Wisely (Marc Jamoulle + ABIM Foundation):

(1) Quaternary prevention (Jamoulle): protect patients from harms of medical intervention itself; avoid overdiagnosis + overtreatment + overuse; primum non nocere;

(2) Overdiagnosis + overdetection: identifying conditions that would not have caused harm — patient labeled as ill; common in cancer screening + incidentalomas; psychological + treatment harms;

(3) Common areas of overuse + low-value care: - Cancer screening: - Screening older adults with limited life expectancy (mammogram, colonoscopy, PSA, Pap); - Aggressive treatment of low-risk cancers (active surveillance better — prostate, DCIS, low-grade thyroid); - Screening outside age guidelines; - Imaging: - Routine imaging for headache, LBP, syncope without red flags; - CT for minor head injury; - Pre-op CXR; - Routine EKG asymptomatic; - Lab tests: - Annual TSH asymptomatic; - Routine vitamin D; - Routine basic labs annual exam without indication; - Medications: - Antibiotics for viral; - PPI long-term without indication; - Antipsychotic in dementia; - Polypharmacy elderly; - Routine antihistamines for cold; - Statin in low-risk elderly with limited life expectancy; - Procedures: - Arthroscopy for OA without mechanical sx; - Vertebroplasty for osteoporotic fractures (controversial); - Routine spinal fusion for chronic LBP; - Pre-op + pre-procedural unnecessary clearance; - Hospital + ICU: - Continuous monitoring not indicated; - Phlebotomy daily routine; - Restraints; - Antibiotic over-broad; - End-of-life ICU when goals palliative; - Mental health: - SSRI for mild grief; - Long-term benzodiazepines; - Stimulant for situational; - Pediatric: - CT for minor head trauma low-risk; - Antibiotic for viral; - Geriatric: - Tight glycemic + BP control elderly with comorbidity; - PSA + colonoscopy elderly; - Polypharmacy;

(4) Choosing Wisely Campaign (ABIM Foundation 2012+): - 80+ specialty societies; - > 600 'don't do' recommendations; - Promotes conversation between clinicians + patients; - Lists for primary care (AAFP, ACP, AAP) + each specialty; - International expansion;

(5) Drivers of overuse: - Defensive medicine — fear of missing or being sued; - Patient expectations — perceived need for test/treatment; - Reimbursement — FFS rewards volume; - Cultural — more is better; - Time pressure — easier to order than discuss; - Lack of clinical decision support; - Direct-to-consumer + medical marketing; - Pharma + device industry influence; - Asymmetric incentives: harms underweighted; - Cascade effect — incidentalomas lead to more testing;

(6) De-implementation strategies: - Audit + feedback; - Clinical decision support alerts; - Shared decision making + decision aids; - Patient + clinician education; - Payment reform (value-based); - Practice + culture change; - Guidelines emphasizing both 'do' and 'don't'; - Practice transformation; - Quality measurement including overuse;

(7) Communication strategies for patients: - Acknowledge concerns + take seriously; - Explain rationale; - Share information about harms + benefits; - Decision aids; - 'Watchful waiting' positive framing; - Specific recommendations; - Follow-up plan; - Empathic + collaborative;

(8) Equity + overuse paradox: - Some communities have both underuse + overuse simultaneously; - Address both; - Underuse in marginalized often more harmful than overuse;

(9) High-value care — provide care of high value (benefit relative to cost + harms): - High-value care principles; - ACP High Value Care Initiative; - Includes prevention, screening, diagnosis, treatment, end-of-life;

(10) Cost transparency + financial toxicity: - Patients suffering from healthcare costs; - Discuss cost when possible; - Choose less costly when comparable benefit; - Generic over brand;

(11) Family medicine well-positioned: relationship, comprehensive view, often non-procedural focus, primary care first principle;

(12) Multidisciplinary: clinicians + patients + administrators + payers + policymakers + societies + advocacy
————————————————
Quaternary prevention: avoid harms of medical intervention. Overuse + low-value care widespread (screening older, imaging routine, abx viral, polypharmacy elderly, etc.). Choosing Wisely. Drivers (defensive, expectations, FFS, time, culture). De-implementation. Shared decision. Equity nuanced. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Documentation Efficiency + Burden Reduction (AAFP + AMA + ONC):

(1) EHR documentation = top driver of burnout + dissatisfaction; PCPs spend ~ 2 h documentation per 1 h direct patient care ('pajama time');

(2) 2021 E/M coding changes (CMS) — major win: - Documentation now based on MDM (Medical Decision-Making) OR total time (not bullet count of history + exam); - Reduces unnecessary documentation; - History + exam at clinically necessary level; - MDM elements: number/complexity of problems + data reviewed/ordered + risk of complications; - Total time includes pre-, intra-, post-visit on date of service;

(3) MDM levels for E/M codes: - 99202 / 99212 — straightforward: minimal problems + minimal data + minimal risk; - 99203 / 99213 — low complexity: 1-2 stable chronic, 1 acute uncomplicated; - 99204 / 99214 — moderate complexity: 1+ chronic with exacerbation OR 2+ stable chronic OR undiagnosed problem; data review; moderate risk (Rx management, MDM); MOST COMMON outpatient PCP code; - 99205 / 99215 — high complexity: severe exacerbation, multiple comorbidity, severe risk (escalation of Rx, hospitalization decision, drug toxicity);

(4) Time-based coding alternative when time > MDM threshold: - 99202: 15-29 min; - 99203: 30-44 min; - 99204: 45-59 min; - 99205: 60-74 min; - Prolonged services add-on codes (99417, G2212); - Includes documentation, chart review, results, calls, coordination on date;

(5) Add-on codes valuable to capture work beyond E/M: - G0444 / G0442 — screening (depression, alcohol); - 99490 / 99487 / G2058 — CCM (chronic care management); - 99495 / 99496 — TCM (transitional care management); - 99497 / 99498 — ACP (advance care planning); - 99484 / 99492-99494 — BHI / CoCM; - 99453 / 99454 / 99457 — RPM (remote patient monitoring);

(6) Strategies for efficient documentation: - SmartPhrases + templates for common conditions, but personalized + accurate; - Voice recognition (Dragon Medical, M*Modal); - Ambient AI scribes (Nuance DAX, Suki, Abridge, Heidi, others) — listen to encounter + draft note + orders + bill suggestions; major productivity boost + burnout reduction; growing rapidly; - Real human scribes (in-person or virtual) — alternative; - Team documentation — MA pre-charting + room prep + reconciliation; - Workflow optimization — pre-visit planning, room layout, EHR settings; - Concurrent vs delayed documentation — concurrent during/immediately after visit better; - Limit copy-forward — keeps notes lean + reduces errors; - Inbox management protocols; - Asynchronous + portal messaging with team triage; - Standing orders + protocols; - EHR optimization + personalization: shortcuts, favorites, dotphrases;

(7) What to include in good notes: - Clinical reasoning; - Patient story + context; - Shared decisions; - Plan + follow-up; - Communication with team / family / specialists; - Relevant social + functional + values; - Avoid: bloat, irrelevant boilerplate, copy-forward of outdated info, copying entire labs;

(8) Documentation for quality + billing: - HCC coding (Hierarchical Condition Categories) for risk adjustment Medicare Advantage; document all chronic conditions annually with specifics; - Quality measures documentation; - Medical necessity; - Avoid undercoding common;

(9) Open notes (OpenNotes movement + Cures Act): - Patients have access to clinical notes; - Write 'for the patient' — clear, non-judgmental, accurate; - Avoid stigmatizing language; - Improves engagement + trust + accuracy; - Address concerns about sensitive topics (mental health, substance use, IPV) — guidance available;

(10) Audit + feedback on documentation + coding;

(11) Provider wellness link: - Reducing documentation burden = wellness intervention; - AI scribes major emerging help; - Team-based care + workflow optimization; - Practice culture supports thoughtful (not excessive) documentation;

(12) Regulatory + future: - Continued reduction in documentation requirements; - Interoperability reduces re-documentation; - AI-driven workflow; - Outcome-focused measurement vs documentation-heavy;

(13) Multidisciplinary: clinicians + scribes/AI + IT + coders + billers + administration + nursing + MA + patients (open notes)
————————————————
Documentation: 2021 E/M MDM or time-based. Add-on codes (CCM, TCM, ACP, BHI, RPM) capture work. Ambient AI scribes major emerging for burden reduction. Open notes — write for patient. Team docs. EHR optimization. HCC for risk adjustment. Wellness link. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Population Health Analytics + Data-Driven Primary Care (CMS + IHI):

(1) Population health management (PHM): proactively manage health outcomes of a defined population — panel, attributed members, community; data + analytics critical;

(2) Data sources: - EHR — clinical, encounters, results, problem lists, medications; - Claims — utilization, costs, full picture across settings (esp ACO); - Registries — chronic disease, specific populations; - HIEs — cross-organization; - Patient-reported data — surveys, PROMs, wearables, portal; - SDOH data — neighborhood, equity-focused; - Public health data — outbreaks, environmental; - Genetic + genomic emerging; - Social media + non-traditional sources;

(3) Analytics capabilities: - Descriptive — what happened? (dashboards, reports); - Diagnostic — why? (drill-down, root cause); - Predictive — what will happen? (risk stratification, ML); - Prescriptive — what should we do? (decision support);

(4) Risk stratification: - High-risk identification — top 5% of users + costs; - Risk algorithms — CMS-HCC, ACG, DxCG, Milliman, custom; combines diagnoses, age, sex, prior utilization, sometimes SDOH; - Rising risk — moderate complexity, intervention can prevent escalation; - Stable + healthy — wellness + prevention; - Apply interventions tailored to risk tier;

(5) Care gaps identification: - HEDIS + similar measures — preventive + chronic disease quality; - Lapsed care — overdue screening, vaccination, lab, follow-up; - Medication adherence — refill data; - Specialty follow-up; - Action: registry-based outreach via call, text, patient portal, mail; standing orders; team-based;

(6) Disease registries: DM, HTN, asthma, CHF, depression, COPD, mental health, substance use, special populations; updated regularly;

(7) Care management programs: - High-risk care management — RN/SW assigned; structured intervention; - Disease management — condition-specific; - Transitional care management (post-hospital); - Behavioral health integration + CoCM (see separate); - Care coordination with specialists, hospital, community;

(8) SDOH integration: - Screening tools (PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, others); - Documentation in EHR; - Resources + referrals (Unite Us, NowPow, FindHelp); - Address actively — partnership with social services + community; - Equity-focused analytics: stratify outcomes;

(9) Quality measurement + reporting: - HEDIS, CMS Stars, MIPS, custom; - Performance dashboards — patient, panel, practice, system levels; - Real-time vs retrospective; - Equity-stratified;

(10) Cost + utilization analytics: - Total cost of care per member; - Utilization — ED, hospitalization, readmission, imaging, specialty; - Pharmacy spend; - Identify outliers + opportunities;

(11) Predictive analytics + ML: - Risk of hospitalization, readmission, mortality; - Disease onset prediction (e.g., HF, AFib, sepsis); - No-show prediction; - Sepsis early detection (controversial — Epic Sepsis Score limitations); - Validation + bias essential;

(12) Patient engagement analytics: - Portal usage, telehealth, app engagement; - PROMs integration; - Survey results (CAHPS, custom);

(13) Workflow integration: - Pre-visit planning — care gaps + chronic disease management; - In-visit — decision support, registries, alerts; - Post-visit — outreach, follow-up; - Between-visit — care management, monitoring;

(14) Provider performance + practice transformation: - Benchmark + variation analysis; - PDSA + improvement projects; - Audit + feedback; - Recognition + incentives;

(15) Equity + bias considerations: - Stratify all metrics by race, ethnicity, language, SES; - Address algorithmic bias; - Community engagement in design; - Avoid widening disparities through interventions;

(16) Workforce + culture: data literacy, quality team, leadership commitment;

(17) Technology infrastructure: EHR + data warehouse + analytics platform; specialized tools (Health Catalyst, Arcadia, Innovaccer, Epic Cogito, others);

(18) Privacy + security: HIPAA, data governance;

(19) Multidisciplinary: clinicians + data analytics + quality + IT + care management + administration + patients + community + payers
————————————————
Population health analytics: data sources (EHR, claims, registries, SDOH). Capabilities (descriptive, predictive, prescriptive). Risk stratification + tailored intervention. Care gaps identification + outreach. Disease registries. Care management. SDOH. Equity-stratified. Workflow integration. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Patient Experience + Satisfaction Primary Care (CAHPS + AHRQ + IHI):

(1) Patient experience vs satisfaction: - Experience: what happened (objective + subjective); - Satisfaction: how patient felt (more variable); - Both matter; experience drives satisfaction + outcomes;

(2) Why patient experience matters: - Outcomes — adherence, follow-through, engagement; - Quality (Triple Aim); - Reduces malpractice (most malpractice = communication failures); - Reimbursement — CMS value-based payment includes; - Reputation + word of mouth; - Provider satisfaction reciprocal;

(3) Measurement: - CAHPS (Consumer Assessment of Healthcare Providers + Systems) — standardized national surveys; multiple versions (clinician + group, PCMH, hospital); - PROMs (patient-reported outcome measures); - NPS (Net Promoter Score) — commercial; - Custom surveys; - Mystery shopping; - Patient advisory councils + qualitative; - Real-time feedback (kiosks, text);

(4) Key drivers of patient experience: - Access — appointment availability, hours, wait times, telemedicine; - Communication — listening, explaining, time spent, partnership; - Care coordination — handoffs, between visits, with specialists; - Provider relationship — continuity, knowing the patient; - Office staff interactions — phones, front desk, MA, nursing; - Physical environment — clean, comfortable, accessible, welcoming; - Patient + family engagement — shared decision-making, materials, portal; - Affordability + financial discussions; - Cultural humility + respect; - Patient safety;

(5) Common dissatisfaction sources: - Waiting time — appointment + in-office; - Communication failures + feeling unheard; - Rushed visits; - Billing issues; - Lack of follow-up on results, plans; - Coordination breakdowns; - Phone access difficult; - Inadequate explanation; - Disrespect or bias; - Financial surprises;

(6) Improvement strategies: - Access: same-day + open access scheduling, after-hours, telemedicine, walk-in options, group visits; - Wait time: workflow optimization, accurate scheduling, communication if delays; - Communication training: empathic listening, NURSE skills, teach-back, shared decision-making; - Continuity: panel size + assignment, follow-up with same provider, care teams; - Team-based care: relationships beyond physician; - Patient portal optimization: secure messaging, schedule, results, refills, bill pay; - Cultural humility + equity: training, diverse workforce, language access, affirming care; - Patient education + materials: plain language, accessible, multiple formats; - Financial transparency + assistance: discussing costs, sliding scale, assistance programs; - Closed-loop on results + follow-up; - Patient + family advisory councils for input; - Service recovery when problems occur — acknowledge, apologize, fix, learn; - Concierge-level touches as appropriate (callback, attentive);

(7) Provider behavior: - Sit at eye level; - Make eye contact (not at screen); - Listen actively + interrupt less (avg 11 sec); - Acknowledge emotions; - Use patient's name; - Explain rationale + recommendations; - Confirm understanding; - Ask 'what questions do you have?'; - Thank patient at end; - Follow through on commitments;

(8) Staff training + culture: - Customer service training for all staff; - Empowerment to resolve issues; - Recognition for good service; - Address turnover + burnout (linked to patient experience);

(9) Specific populations: - Limited English — interpreter services + accommodations; - Disabilities — accessibility; - Pediatric — child + parent considerations; - Mental health + sensitive issues — trauma-informed + safe environment; - LGBTQ+ — affirming; - Older adults — pace + considerations;

(10) Outcomes link: better experience → better adherence + outcomes + reduced utilization;

(11) Equity in patient experience: - Disparities in experience documented (e.g., race, language); - Stratify metrics; - Address gaps;

(12) Provider wellness link: positive experiences for both — bidirectional; reduce burnout helps both;

(13) Multidisciplinary patient experience team: leadership + clinicians + staff + patients (advisory) + quality + facilities + IT + customer service
————————————————
Patient experience: matters for outcomes + reimbursement + reputation. CAHPS measurement. Drivers (access, communication, coordination, relationship, staff). Improvement (access, training, continuity, portal, transparency, advisory). Provider behavior. Equity in experience. Wellness link. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Social Prescribing + SDOH Integration (NHS + WHO + US emerging):

(1) Social prescribing (originated NHS UK, growing US): primary care refers patients to non-medical community-based services for biopsychosocial needs;

(2) Common social prescriptions: - Food: meal delivery (Meals on Wheels), food pantry, SNAP/WIC assistance, food prescriptions (produce vouchers), nutrition counseling; - Housing: housing assistance, supportive housing, weatherization, lead abatement, mold remediation, Section 8, homelessness services; - Transportation: ride services (Lyft, Uber Health), public transit assistance, paratransit; - Financial: benefits enrollment (Medicaid, SNAP, SSI, EITC), financial counseling, debt management, employment assistance; - Legal: medical-legal partnerships (housing, immigration, benefits, family); - Education: GED, literacy, English language; - Childcare: subsidies, programs; - Connection: community groups, religious communities, peer support, intergenerational, hobby + interest; - Exercise + activity: parks programs, gym referrals (SilverSneakers, YMCA), walking groups, gardening, tai chi; - Mental health adjuncts: art, music, dance, drama therapy, mindfulness, gardening, nature exposure; - Spiritual + religious: chaplaincy, faith communities, meditation, contemplative practices;

(3) Implementation models: - Screen first: standardized SDOH tools (PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, 'Health Begins'); - Care navigator / community health worker / link worker: bridges referrals + follows up; - Community resource platforms: Unite Us, NowPow, FindHelp.org, Aunt Bertha — directories + referrals + closed-loop tracking; - Embedded community resources — co-location of social services, legal, financial; - Co-design with community;

(4) Why integrate SDOH: - 80% of health outcomes from SDOH (vs 20% medical); - Address root causes; - Improve outcomes + equity; - Reduce utilization + costs (some evidence); - Patient-centered care; - Required for value-based care; - Some payment models incentivize;

(5) CMS + Medicaid increasingly addressing: - Z codes documentation in EHR (ICD-10 Z55-Z65 — SDOH); - Medicaid 1115 waivers for SDOH; - In Lieu Of services Medicaid; - CMS Innovation Center models (REACH ACO, others) incentivize; - Quality measures including SDOH;

(6) Evidence base: - Food prescriptions — improved DM, BP, food security; - Housing interventions (Housing First) — better mental health, substance use, hospitalization, cost; - Transportation — improved appointment attendance + outcomes; - Medical-legal partnerships — improved health + cost; - Community health workers — multiple conditions; - Social prescribing UK — improved well-being, reduced primary care visits, some cost reduction;

(7) Workforce: - Community Health Workers (CHWs) — bridge community + healthcare; trained; growing recognition + reimbursement; - Social workers; - Care navigators / patient advocates; - Promotores / lay health workers; - Peer support specialists (especially mental health, substance use, lived experience); - Medical-legal partners;

(8) Community partnerships essential: - Food banks, housing organizations, schools, faith-based, parks + recreation, libraries, employers, government agencies, social services, advocacy; - Asset-based community development approach — leverage strengths; - Coalitions + collaboratives; - Community input + governance;

(9) Ethical + privacy considerations: - Asking sensitive SDOH questions — trauma-informed; - Risk of stigma if SDOH discovered + not addressed; - Confidentiality with community partners; - Data sharing agreements;

(10) Equity + community engagement: - Power dynamics + structural racism in design; - Community co-design; - Hire from community; - Equity in resource access;

(11) Sustainability + funding: - Operational challenges; - Reimbursement evolving; - Grant funding; - Health system investment + benefit; - Policy advocacy;

(12) Quality measurement + outcomes: - Patient experience; - Resource connection + utilization; - Health outcomes (chronic disease, mental health, hospitalization); - Equity stratified; - Cost;

(13) Resources: SIREN (UCSF Social Interventions Research + Evaluation Network), Aligning for Health, AAFP EveryONE Project, Camden Coalition;

(14) Multidisciplinary: PCP + CHW + social work + behavioral health + community partners + government + nonprofits + faith + business + patients + advocacy
————————————————
Social prescribing + SDOH: 80% outcomes from social factors. Screen (PRAPARE), connect via navigator + platforms (Unite Us). Common prescriptions (food, housing, transportation, financial, social, exercise, mental health). Evidence-based interventions. CHW + community partnerships. CMS Z codes + payment. Equity + community co-design. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Multi-Generational Family-Centered Chronic Disease (AAFP + family medicine principles):

(1) Family medicine unique value: care entire family unit; understand interactions + dynamics; relationship continuity; address upstream + interconnected health;

(2) Multi-generational chronic disease common: - Children: T1DM, asthma, ADHD, autism, mental health, obesity, allergies, dental; - Parents + working age: T2DM, HTN, lipid, obesity, depression, anxiety, substance use, autoimmune, chronic pain; caregivers; - Grandparents + elderly: dementia, frailty, multimorbidity, isolation; care recipients; - All ages: vaccinations, preventive, mental health, dental, vision;

(3) Family-level assessment: - Genogram 3 generations — medical, mental health, social, relationships; - Family roles + dynamics; - Caregiving structure + burden; - Communication patterns; - Financial + housing; - Cultural + religious; - ACEs across generations; - Strengths + resilience;

(4) Coordinated visits + communication: - Family meetings for major decisions, transitions, end-of-life; - Sibling visits or coordinated; - Shared appointments for elderly + caregiver; - Care plans visible to family with consent; - Multi-generational EHR view (within HIPAA);

(5) Caregiver support critical: - Identify + screen caregivers in patient visits (Zarit Burden); - Caregiver-specific visits with own goals; - Education + training; - Respite resources (in-home, adult day care, short-term residential); - Support groups (specific to condition — Alzheimer's Association, etc.); - Mental health support — caregiver depression, anxiety; - Practical assistance: caregiving leave (FMLA), financial planning, legal (POA, advance directives); - Self-care + boundaries; - Recognize caregiver burnout, abuse, neglect; - Sandwich generation: caring for both children + parents — high stress; - Hidden caregivers: spouses, children, distant family;

(6) Pediatric chronic disease in family context: - T1DM (this scenario): family involvement essential — coordinated diabetes management, sibling impact, parental burnout, transition to self-management adolescence + adult care; - Family-based behavioral interventions evidence (T2DM, asthma, mental health, weight management); - School integration; - Anticipatory guidance: developmental + chronic disease; - Mental health screening for child + family;

(7) Adult chronic disease in family context: - Spouse/partner involvement: motivation, support, shared decision-making; - Spouse health affected by partner illness (caregiver burden, increased risk own illness); - Sexual + intimacy considerations; - Children affected: especially if young + parental chronic illness; - Financial impact on family; - Lifestyle changes family-wide (diet, exercise, smoking) more sustainable;

(8) Geriatric in family context: - Caregiver-centered model of care; - Adult children involved in decisions (with patient consent + when capacity declines); - Sibling coordination; - Long-distance caregiving; - Transitions: aging in place vs assisted living vs nursing home — family discussions; - Advance care planning + family meetings; - End-of-life care; - Bereavement affects whole family;

(9) Family-based interventions evidence: - CBT + family therapy; - Family-based diabetes education; - Family asthma programs; - Family-based weight management; - Family meals + nutrition; - Family physical activity; - Parenting programs (PCIT, Triple P) for behavior; - Caregiver education + support; - Genetic family counseling;

(10) Cultural + diverse families: - Definitions of family vary — chosen family, extended, multigenerational households, LGBTQ+ families, single-parent, blended, foster + adoptive; - Cultural roles + decision-making vary; - Language + literacy; - Religious + spiritual beliefs about health + healing; - Affirming care for diverse family structures;

(11) Adverse family experiences: - IPV; - Child abuse + neglect; - Elder abuse; - Substance use in family; - Mental illness affecting family; - Divorce + separation; - Death; - Trauma transmission; - Mandatory reporting when applicable; - Trauma-informed family-centered care;

(12) Resources: family caregiver alliance, AARP caregiving, Alzheimer's Association, NAMI for family of mentally ill, specific disease foundations, MyAgingParent, etc.;

(13) Multidisciplinary family-centered: family medicine + relevant specialty + behavioral health + social work + nursing + dietitian + caregivers + family + community + faith + legal + financial
————————————————
Multi-generational family-centered: family medicine unique value. Genogram + family assessment. Coordinated visits + communication. Caregiver support critical. Pediatric / adult / geriatric chronic disease in family context. Family-based interventions evidence. Cultural diversity. Adverse experiences. Multidisciplinary.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Workplace Wellness + Occupational Health Integrative (NIOSH + ACOEM + WHO):

(1) Workplace impact on health: - Working-age adults spend 1/3 of waking hours at work; - Workplace exposures + culture significant determinant of health; - Workplace wellness can leverage scale + structure; - Integration with primary care;

(2) Common occupational exposures + concerns: - Physical: ergonomic (MSK injuries), noise (hearing loss), heat/cold, radiation, vibration, falls, motor vehicle (commercial drivers), needle sticks + bloodborne (healthcare); - Chemical: solvents, metals, pesticides, fumes, particulates, endocrine disruptors, asbestos (historical); - Biological: infectious (healthcare, food, animal handling, public-facing) — COVID-19 huge example; - Psychosocial: workplace stress, harassment, discrimination, demands, lack of control, work-life conflict, bullying, violence; - Shift work: circadian disruption, sleep, CV, GI, cancer (IARC 2A); - Sedentary work: prolonged sitting; - Computer-related: vision, MSK, repetitive strain; - Pregnancy + reproductive: certain exposures + accommodations;

(3) OSHA + regulatory framework: - OSHA standards + enforcement; - NIOSH research + recommendations; - MSHA mining; - Worker's compensation state-based; - EEOC (discrimination + ADA accommodations); - FMLA (family + medical leave);

(4) Occupational history taking in primary care: - All jobs (current + past); - Specific exposures; - Onset of symptoms relationship; - Work hazards; - PPE use; - Workplace incidents; - Co-workers similarly affected; - Job demands + accommodations; - Returns to work;

(5) Specific occupational conditions: - MSK injuries: ergonomics + return-to-work; - Hearing loss noise-induced — prevention + hearing conservation programs; - Asthma work-exacerbated or sensitizer-induced; - Dermatitis occupational; - Mental health + burnout + workplace stress + violence; - Heat-related illness; - Bloodborne pathogen exposure (healthcare needle stick); - Pesticide exposure (agricultural workers); - Pneumoconioses (silicosis, asbestosis, coal worker's, byssinosis); - Hand-arm vibration syndrome; - Carpal tunnel work-related; - Lead, mercury, other heavy metal poisoning;

(6) Workplace wellness programs: - Comprehensive programs: health risk assessment, biometric screening, lifestyle coaching, smoking cessation, weight management, exercise, nutrition, stress, financial wellness; - Evidence mixed: some show modest health improvement + ROI; selection bias common; - Equity considerations: not all employees benefit equally; access + privacy concerns; - Voluntary + privacy important; - Tobacco-free workplace, healthy food options, lactation rooms (ACA required), exercise facilities; - Employee Assistance Programs (EAP) — confidential counseling, financial, legal, family; - Mental health benefits + access;

(7) Return to work after illness/injury: - Modified duty / light duty preferred over total disability when possible; - Functional capacity evaluation; - Graduated return-to-work; - Accommodations under ADA; - Communication with employer (with consent);

(8) Workers' Compensation: - Insurance system for work injuries; - Documentation requirements; - Disability ratings; - Treatment authorization; - Litigation considerations; - State-specific;

(9) Vulnerable workers: - Low-wage; - Immigrant + undocumented (special protections + barriers); - Temporary + gig workers; - Healthcare workers (high physical + emotional + infectious + violence risks); - Older workers; - Pregnant workers (PWFA 2022 expanded accommodations); - People with disabilities (ADA);

(10) Pandemic / COVID-19 workplace: - PPE; - Telework expansion; - Ventilation; - Vaccination policies; - Quarantine + sick leave; - Long COVID; - Mental health impact;

(11) Climate change + workplace: heat stress increasing; outdoor workers;

(12) Public health + workplace intersection: - Workplace COVID outbreaks; - Smoke-free workplace legislation; - Workplace as health promotion site;

(13) Provider role: - Recognize occupational causes; - Counsel + accommodations; - Coordinate workers' compensation; - Workplace contact with consent; - Report required conditions (lead, certain infectious, occupational injuries); - Advocate for safe workplaces;

(14) Resources: NIOSH, OSHA, ACOEM, AOEC + others;

(15) Multidisciplinary: PCP + occupational medicine + employer + HR + safety + employee + union (where applicable) + ADA coordinator + workers' comp + community + advocacy
