ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด): Bereavement + Grief — Primary Care (NHPCO + APA):

(1) Grief is normal universal response to loss, not pathology; primary care often first contact + ongoing support;

(2) Types of loss requiring grief support: - Death (spouse, parent, child, sibling, friend); - Anticipatory (chronic/terminal illness); - Disenfranchised (LGBTQ+, miscarriage, pet, dementia, addiction); - Trauma + sudden death; - Mass casualty + disaster; - Estrangement; - Loss of health, function, role, dreams;

(3) Normal grief manifestations: - Emotional: sadness, anger, guilt, anxiety, relief, numbness, loneliness, yearning; - Physical: fatigue, sleep, appetite, somatic symptoms, immune effects (broken heart syndrome, takotsubo); - Cognitive: difficulty concentrating, preoccupation, denial, confusion; - Behavioral: withdrawal, crying, restlessness, dreams; - Spiritual: questioning faith, meaning, anger at higher power; - Social: changes in relationships + role;

(4) Theories of grief (no rigid stages, individualized): - Kübler-Ross stages (originally for dying, applied to grief — controversial application): denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance; - Worden's tasks: accept reality, process pain, adjust to environment without, find way to memorialize + move forward; - Dual process model (Stroebe + Schut): oscillation between loss-oriented + restoration-oriented; - Continuing bonds (Klass): healthy ongoing connection; - Meaning-making (Neimeyer);

(5) Distinguishing normal vs complicated grief: - Normal: intensity decreases over time; functions; finds meaning; bonds with deceased + new connections; - Acute grief: weeks-months, intense; - Integrated grief: continues lifetime; - Prolonged grief disorder (PGD) DSM-5-TR (2022 added): - Persistent intense grief > 12 mo adults / > 6 mo children; - Identity disruption; - Disbelief; - Avoidance; - Emotional pain; - Difficulty engaging; - Numbness; - Loss of meaning; - Loneliness; - ~ 7-10% bereaved; - Risk factors: traumatic death, close attachment, prior trauma, lack of support; - Treatment: complicated grief therapy (Shear), targeted CBT, group, medications selected; - Major depressive disorder comorbid + distinct from normal grief — treat both; - PTSD especially traumatic death;

(6) Suicide risk elevated in bereaved (especially spouse, parent loss, first weeks-months, suicide bereavement); screen;

(7) Primary care role: - Continued relationship + presence; - Active listening + validation — primary intervention; - Education — normalize grief; - Screening — depression, suicidal ideation, complicated grief; - Pharmacotherapy — judicious; SSRI for comorbid depression or PGD with depression; avoid benzodiazepines (mask grief, dependence); short-term sleep aid if needed; - Referral — therapist, complicated grief specialist, support groups, hospice bereavement; - Address physical concerns that may arise; - Spiritual support referral;

(8) Bereavement support resources: - Hospice bereavement programs — 13 months Medicare hospice benefit; - Support groups: condition-specific, demographic-specific (widows, parents of children who died, suicide loss survivors — TAPS for military, Compassionate Friends for child loss, others); - Online communities; - Faith communities; - Caring contacts (cards, calls); - Workplace bereavement leave + support; - Anniversary reactions awareness;

(9) Children + adolescents grieving: - Developmentally specific responses; - Age-appropriate explanations; - Continued routines + reassurance; - School involvement; - Children of grieving parents — additional support; - Resources: National Alliance for Children's Grief, Dougy Center;

(10) Special populations: - Pregnant + perinatal loss (miscarriage, stillbirth, neonatal) — often disenfranchised; specific support (Star Legacy, others); - LGBTQ+ — disenfranchised grief if not recognized; chosen family; - Suicide loss survivors — high risk PGD + own suicide; specific support (AFSP); - Substance use loss — disenfranchised; - Mass casualty / disaster — community response; - Healthcare worker grief: cumulative loss, moral injury, peer support; - COVID-19 bereaved — large group, often complicated by isolation + restrictions;

(11) Cultural + spiritual considerations: - Diverse rituals + practices; - Mourning periods + customs; - Respect + accommodate; - Religious traditions + clergy involvement; - Continuing bonds vary culturally;

(12) Provider self-care + own grief: - Accumulating losses; - Patient deaths; - Peer support + debriefing; - Acknowledge own grief;

(13) Multidisciplinary: PCP + behavioral health + chaplaincy + social work + bereavement specialists + community resources + support groups + family + friends + faith community + workplace
————————————————
Bereavement / grief: normal universal response. Types + manifestations. Distinguish normal vs prolonged grief disorder (DSM-5-TR 2022). Comorbid depression + PTSD + suicide risk. PC role: presence, validation, education, screening, judicious meds (SSRI for comorbid), referrals. Resources + support groups. Special populations. Cultural humility. Provider self-care. Multidisciplinary.

